Ok, I love your channel. Just makes me broaden my horizons and think about many things I never did.  As a cis woman, I've often wondered about genders, even when I was a kid and wanted to dress like a guy, to see how it is. Now this video made me think about the following: what is actually the essence of the female? It's obviously not our bodies, or how we were brought up. It's not our voices, or our breasts. It's not our character or attitude. It's not the supposed ability to give birth (as more and more women find that they can't conceive nowadays, me included). It's not a certain sexuality. These are all variables. What is the thing that makes me a woman? What makes me similar to other women - both cis and trans? What unites us? I don't believe in a having a soul, but then what is it? According to some members of society, a woman is only a woman when she has a certain level of attractiveness according to someone, but I believe that this is something forced on us externally and do not consider it a real criterion.  So what is it? What's the real essence of a woman? If there were two brains in jars, hooked to a computer, how would we tell, and would it matter, which one was the female one, and would there be any actual difference? I'd really love to hear someone's opinion on this.

I was recalling this video the other day and it struck me how much the very core of intellectual debates nowadays is primarily filtered and analysed through aesthetic lenses. 'Antifeminist calmly dismantles feminism'-type videos/circlejerks, the smooth and collected speech of people explaining why racism c'mon guys it isn't so bad is it, then the instant invalidation of any arguments made with any shred of underlying emotion or the mocking of any minority of marginalized group when they display discontent with any given situation. It is first and foremost an aesthetic judgement. The argument is not that important; as long as the person sounds distanced and presents their ideas in a soothing, ASMR-like monotone, it will be a valid point of view. You do have outliers who are more on the failed stand-up comedian end of the spectrum like LaPaglia, but it's only natural that the easily-triggered snowflake-conservatives will want vary and to find the odd avatar to their habitual rants and fits.

My personal experience tells me that gender identity is not a performance, or a role that one plays in society. It's not a social construct, but rather, it's a part of reproductive biology. We instinctively make efforts to identify the sex of people we meet, and we're driven a little crazy when we can't (see any 'It's Pat' segment from Saturday Night Live). But that instinct doesn't just apply to others, it applies to ourselves, too. And the information we seek (as to our own sex) is already inscribed in the brain, biologically, before we're even born.   It makes sense to think that knowing both our own sex and the sex of those we meet is supposed to affect which mates we're attracted to, but that obviously isn't always the deciding factor. It does seem to work that way for most people, though.   But the point is, my female identity isn't linked to any social construct. Not to girly clothes, or mannerisms, or role. If I could wave a magic wand and turn myself into a woman (a recurring fantasy of mine), I'd still mostly wear the same kind of clothes. I'd keep my hair short. I'd walk with a masculine gait. Like I already do. Because if I didn't like to behave that way, I already wouldn't. I'm a very masculine woman trapped in a man's body. You'd think that'd make things easier, but it doesn't; it's still maddening. Worse, transitioning would be less helpful, because with the technology of today, what does it even mean to transition from a man into a butch lesbian? It's pretty much only the parts that I want to change (like my hairline, voice, height, bone structure, and proportions) that I can't. And so I'm stuck waiting for the technology to improve.

I totally have that kind of inner dialogue with myself. A lot. I'm not arguing with myself as much anymore though, cause I've already found my happy (actually conflicted) middle ground. I'm not a trans woman but I relate to a lot of that social aspect (in general) cause of my detransition from ftm. I'm still happy with most of the things testosterone gave me, but I realised I am not and was never a man. I really love being a woman now, although some things suck about it.   But I don't pass for shite. That phrase about bearded women with deep voices made me chuckle cause that's where I'm at now in life. And I love it. I love my voice, my beard, my vagina and my wide hips. I just miss my boobs. So that's the only medical detransition procedure I actually want to do (except I did go off the hrt as well). As in breast reconstruction to 'reverse' my top surgery. But except from my boobs, I also miss being seen as a woman in public. The fuck did I throw that away for? Now I can't have it back again. Not without sacrificing parts of my body that bring me comfort and help me sleep at night. And I know I can't do that.   If it's not clear, I'm not against anyone transitioning. I'm not even clearly against *me* having transitioned. I empathise with trans women. Cause at least I now understand how uncomfortable (and sometimes scary) it can often be to be read as a gnc (cis) man to strangers when you're actually a woman. That's a new kind of lump in my throat. Walking around in public with a beard and boobs in the same, neatly thought-out, feminine outfit has me shaking my own damn head about how I ended up here and where the fuck I'm heading in life. I love the way I look, but I hate the social consequences of it.  Ultimately I did decide to stay non-passing. I mean, if I can cope with the social implications of that in the long run. And that's what I'm mostly debating with myself about.   *Is it worth it, to really ditch the option of ever looking like a woman again, because I now love my masculinised body? Yeah... yes, it is.* Cause achieving self-love was my ultimate goal of transitioning, and somehow I reached it in detransition. Approval of others will never triumph self-love. But I don't think it will ever stop being painful, cause it's still a huge loss. I was a woman, and I miss her. Even though I've always been her and still am, hidden in plain sight.

I'm a cis woman who has had difficulty with feeling like I'm not always feminine enough. Though it's highly unlikely I'll ever be mistaken for a man, my fears of even appearing manly have often stopped me in the past from playing male characters in school plays, just incase I'm nearly too convincing and people start to see me as masculine when I only wanted to be seen as feminine. It's not the same thing as what trans women feel but I sympathise with how they do feel that urge to be always taken as female and become more feminine than cis women. I think it's a hard line to walk between the freedom you want to have to be yourself at all times and the desire to be perceived as feminine at all times because just being a woman doesn't always mean being feminine and not all women want to be feminine either. But the most secure and confident feminine women can also express their masculinity too when they feel they should. That's why Disneys Mulan is one of my heroes.

I LIVE FOR THIS VIDEO  As for myself as a trans woman I LOVE this video as it echoed the two-ness that I experience everyday that I hate to admit to myself. Aesthetics matter to me because they matter to everyone else I'm trying to convince I am what I am while simultaneously I want to push who I really am rather than who I am percieved to be. I want to remain analogous in my presentation because I want to be like 'everybody else' but I want to stay distinct in order to promote to me-ness that is me. Trying to accomplish this in practice is super difficult. It's so much fun dressing like a barbie and showing up to fighting game tournaments and hip hop show. 'Thanks! I hate it!' - Lindsey Ellis. And even coming to terms with that...  I like looking like a barbie, but I hate that thag is how I want to present myself knowing that it is a shallow repetition of 'womanhood' from the dress, the makeup, even my mannerisms. This two-ness its stifling and stressful and while this fails as a dialect, it succeeds as a study of character. Like the play/film 'The Sunset Limited'   I posted this similar response to letstalkaboutstuff, but I wanted to let you know as well. One must be objective in order to delineate what is truth and feeling. And the real T is that we all experience and that is why we feel some type of way when its put in front of us. I know I did and immediately was like 'damn, how much if my trans-ness is me and what I feel ik expected to perform?' It haunts me. I could be tabby, but then.... the eyes..... shallow, yes. But same thing for me being a person of color. How much is me and how much is my performance? Worse so for you because of your celebrity having to perform for people like me and those who are NOT me on top of the two-ness of the trans life. Well, such is life.   Anyways, love love love it and thank thank thank you so so so much. Please dont stop. Keep it coming. Just like this and more. Educate without question or pause.  P.S. Cis people should watch it to gain this understanding of self conflict to produce a product THEY are willing or even able to digest.

I think that this debate, while being all the more deadly serious to the effect of transness, is central to 'successful womanhood' in and of itself. As a first-generation college student, and a cis woman of color from a low socio-economic background, I've found that 'performing' my gender in a way that conforms to the reigning ideals of white femininity has been essential in my bids for success in the academic and professional worlds that are slanted against me. There is a need to be ultra-polished and ultra-hardworking to earn respect at the same level as others.    When I first accepted a scholarship to a prestigious university, I was an intelligent, yet socially awkward girl with hand-me-down clothes who hated makeup. As a senior, I rarely feel comfortable stepping out without a full face, styled hair, and a coordinated outfit. I hear myself talk sometimes about studying abroad, networking, internships that I've done... And when I'm at home with my family, I feel the disconnect; I almost don't recognize who I've become.   So, at the core of my experience w femininity, there is this struggle between my authentic self and wanting to subvert the oppressive culture that I belong to, and the necessity to conform in order to be accepted and thrive.

The aesthetic... I'm not trans, but I am bi and was in denial for a long time. I was essentially my own bully. I came out at around 22 and always regretted not coming out sooner. But attending Catholic school, and being in society in general, and having friends that just would casually use gay slurs, constant jokes on tv. I never felt even close to comfortable acknowledging that side of myself. To do so would be a social death sentence, and I was already socially destitute. Even to this day I have trust issues with close friends. I feel like I never know their true intentions no matter how clear they make them. Plenty of straight people will use the word f***** as a bludgeon if they feel even remotely challenged on any of their preconceived notions. This constant need to be on guard, to act and present a certain way with my emotions and always pay attention to how others perceive me... it's exhausting. It must be way harder for a trans person. Like, speaking of gay boys on instagram, I wish I had been one. There's a huge part of me that felt I never had the chance to totally own who I was. It was robbed from me by a cruel and indifferent society. Coming out earlier would have been like trial by fire. Kind of a lose-lose scenario. But more power to those who can do it. It sucks having to wait, whether you're gay or trans or anything.

So... you're basically saying that what you are must always be based on other's perception of you? I mean, I'm not naive enough to say that this notion is not partially correct, but to consciously act that way is a bit... pointlessly straining. We live in the age of the internet! At least one group of people out there won't care, doesn't understand, or doesn't know who you are, no matter if you have thirteen copies of an official medical degree stamped to your chest. Even if who you 'really' are is a fantasy, if you try to fashion yourself into the belonging kind of the entire internet or even a single village, it is always *you* that will be sacrificed. Doesn't that undermine the whole point of trying to gender yourself in the first place? The whole point being that you want people to treat you how you really feel? The comfort in finding people who accept and understand you? And if you really don't want to convince the world who you are, shouldn't you just find a small group of friends or family that can relate to you and support you? That seems much more effective for your emotional health.  A counterargument could be made against the very notion of this performance itself. But that's just my opinion... It hardly matters in broad overarching societal norms... But maybe fighting those norms from the ground up is how we get society to change.

But main point is trans women are still treated as women even if not viewed as True Women by transphobes. you know, i just found this channel a couple weeks ago. I didn't know why i kept watching at first, but i feel like i see something in her videos:  a conflict inside herself. I identify as male, but there are many times when i question whether the things i do and the way i appear are masculine enough. Despite being 'cisgender' there are times when i strongly question if i am 'playing' the role of man enough. Is my inner experience what makes me a man? Is it my genitals? is my masculinity durable enough for me to wear things i like even though they are 'cute' and thus 'non-manly'? These are questions i've come up with verbal answers to and been reassured by others of, but the internal debate and doubts still linger.  This video feels to me like an expression of anguish over such internalized questioning of gender identity vs gender expression. Like part of her feels a NEED to be glam and present strongly as typically feminine while part of her wants to outright reject that as it's harmful and bad. Honestly, I prefer the poetry of Sappho over that of teenage gay boys on Instagram. But that's mainly because I haven't been on Instagram in more years than the months this video has been up.  As to actual philosophical discourse on aesthetics...it's a balance. You point out color-matching style theory with the exact same color wheel I have similarly hanging on my wall. And that's significant in representing the idea of conformity to others' views, as failing to mix tones and tints properly yields garish content even within the context of different cultural or countercultural identities. (For a younger audience, I recommend googling for a glimpse into 90's 'fashion'. So many splotches of random vibrant colors everywhere! It was like a unicorn got so drunk that it started vomiting rainbows...that was an awesome time to be a kid!)  However, there's the explicit element of personal identification. People buy what they like, and obviously are going to wear what they buy so they literally ought to be wearing what they like. Plus some rationalizing to invert the sentiment such that 'people ought to like what they wear' becomes a second conclusion, but I'm a philosopher so I don't need to go through all the steps to get to the conclusion if people agree with it. (Nah, I'm just kidding. This second conclusion is instead actually reached from the starting point of acknowledging individual taste and personal preferences as valid acceptable precepts or a foundation taken 'a priori' without contention.)  -----  A person who wishes to earn respect (or other forms of social power) must be willing to balance what they want to (in this case) wear with what other people believe about (in this case) the outfit as a whole and in composition. So I can speak pretty bluntly that you won't see me in vibrant 'Hawaiian shirts', and that I will very rarely wear a suit because I don't actually like suits. I can also say confidently that if I wear a suit, unless it's for something like a funeral for someone I cared about, it's probably gonna be a bright or flamboyant combination.  And, taking from music, there's nothing wrong with being 'underground' or 'alternative'. They may not have an excessive hold on mainstream presence, but they can fill a gap or niche that the 'normal' conventions don't necessarily provide. However, the corollary to this is that such 'alternative' status permits less leniency in terms of what is socially allowed to be gotten away with. Ozzy Osbourne can do a lot more 'wrong' than Rob Zombie before people start criticizing the former; as an example.

I have no insecurity about my gender, so it seems like a waste of time, energy, and resources to do expensive things to my body to make other people perceive me more accurately. (Granted that I did pass flawlessly for male as a teenager, so I do have a formative lived experience of social masculinity bolstering my internal self-knowledge.) My brain is something that physically exists in nature and my consciousness is a thing that's happening regardless of whether others understand a single thing about it. No one is ever able to experience another person's consciousness anyway. We are all alone. So someone else understanding what I am, or misunderstanding what I am, is a separate event from my own existence.   I agree w/ Natalie that since I only communicate my masculinity verbally and in my mannerisms/behavior, no one fully, consistently perceives me as a man while interacting with me, and so my maleness it will never be truly manifested in the space between me and any other person I interact with unless I transition (which I am seriously considering right now, because it's difficult to date people when you're in a biological form of drag 24/7). But why is the space between me and another person more 'real' than the space in my own head? Both these spaces are metaphysical, not really real; they're just events that happen. So I just had a revelation about this video.  This video triggered me pretty badly when I first watched (listened) to it, but I was confused about what was bothering me so much. I thought it had to do with the dismissal of nonconforming women, because of the subject matter; but frankly, I'm used to that shit by now and I don't normally feel like I have any trauma attached to it.  Today, it hit me. It wasn't the subject of The Aesthetic that bothered me. It was the depiction of the relationship between the two women, which reminds me in many respects of an abusive friendship that dominated my childhood.  The conversation consists largely of Justine bullying Tabby, *ostensibly for her own good*. The normally forthright, self-willed Tabby is reduced to nearly silence, apparently cowed by Justine. Justine belittles her, insults her, and dismisses her priorities, values, and choices about her own body with a wave of her hand, substituting her own; and Tabby argues a little, but ultimately defers. It's for her own good, after all. Justine is just telling the *hard truths*.   The 'truths' in question? That everyone thinks she's weird. That she makes everyone uncomfortable. That no one will accept her the way she is. That Justine is the only person *willing* to be her friend. That Justine is doing her a favor by belittling her and breaking her down. That all of her bullying is just because she's trying to mold her into a person that other people will be able to tolerate or take seriously. That Tabby has to conform to Justine's ideas of how to live her life if she ever wants to be friends with anyone else.  There's no intimacy between these two characters. No indication that Justine actually cares about Tabby qua Tabby. No indication that Tabby feels anything but uncomfortable. Sure, Justine may claim to love her. But she's claiming that at the end of a video consisting primarily of tearing her down 'for her own good.' It's classic gaslighting.  Natalie said on Twitter that she intended this video as an examination of how trans women talk among themselves. She implied that she has her own Justine-equivalent, who taught her the importance of being glamorous to being taken seriously. I really, really hope that the relationship portrayed on screen is nothing like any relationship that Natalie may have in real life; because I've been there, and it is not healthy.

think Justine had the better argument, but Tabby had the moral high ground. Ultimately, the entire video is just a metaphor for the continued struggle between idealists (Tabby) and realists (Justine).  People talking about who win are missing the larger point though; there's not suppose to be a winner here. The true purpose of dialogue is to understand the other viewpoint, and it's always been my opinion that when you can truly do so, conceding some of your vision (right or wrong) to reach a higher quorum of opinion, you make a stronger movement. Mainstream feminists (and liberals) have as much to learn from radical feminists (and socialists) as they do them. I'm not arguing for a completely centerist view, but one which is more center than the current popular bipolar dichotomy.

I honestly think Jung's ideas about archetypes and 'primordial images' may be the direction for the gender debate to go through. I don't necessarily mean his theory of anima/animus. You're dealing with categories--man/woman--that exist yet have no strict qualities or criteria. Archetypes are based on millions of years of evolutionary experience and don't conform to any specific cultural norm. 'Woman' is a concept not based on a list of criteria, but millions of years of observation and practice of tangible living examples. Thus, like all archetypes, 'you know it when you see it.' As in, you FEEL it. It's primal instinct.   If we allow gender to be a primordial image (for which there is no attack helicopter category), we avoid basing it on current gender roles, stereotypes, or ideals, even though those things may overlap. We also give it an evolutionary foundation. What's interesting about this is that archetypes are a collective image, which mirrors Justine's point about gender being a social construct, but still does not validate the notion that it has to be performed or earned in any specific way. But, at the same time, there exist certain qualities that cue our instinct to distinguish between male and female, but they are too complex to put into words (which leads to stereotyping).

This post is originally a response to Maria the Witch's video in response to this one, but I believe this deserves to be here, too. Maybe Natalie will read it, and let me know how much of my interpretation is wrong.     To Maria: I think you have missed the point Natalie is attempting to make. And I will refer to only the dialectic rather than the mock TV interview, as I feel that was only illustration and background to the dialectic. While I certainly can not speak for her, I am rather certain that she is aware of the problematic stance that Justine is taking. But she is also aware of the problematic stance of Tabby. Those of us (trans women) who have the privilege (as unfortunate as it is to have to call that privilege) to be seen, of which I am not one, represent us all. As an activist, Natalie is well seen, and knows that what she does reflects on all of us. The dialectic is between two of Natalie's inner monologues. Tabby, the radical idealist, doesn't care what anyone thinks, dresses and acts impulsively, however suits her. All of us admire that ideal, and know that is the way things should be. Justine, the pragmatic materialist, is chiding Tabby not for her own appearance, but for her public appearance that represents all of us. She at first extols the virtues of putting on a false face for the sake of everyone she represents, is rebuffed (correctly) by Tabby and admits she had gone to far, but continues to hold some belief in making some personal sacrifice for the sake of the cause. In the end, she reaches no conclusions, both sides unhappily accepting a difficult draw, and sits back to watch the angry YouTube comments and experience the state of the world unhappily. Her video provides no answers, I believe, because that was her point. Natalie has no answers, she doesn't know how to represent best a disparate community fighting for acceptance. What she does know is that both sides of her dialectic must make compromises. She knows that trans people can not, no matter how much we would like to, win acceptance on our own. No group ever has. You must kill the enemy softly. I hope I do her point justice, and I hope I am not to far off the mark.

The idea of performativity is pure stupidity. It is intentionalism trying to grapple with the contingency of its operations in the face of scientific protocols that track deep, causal relationships. As such, it marks the collapse of the reality principle, which was only effective in certain cognitive ecologies given sufficient invariance. This is a common debate amongst people in marginalized groups. To what extent do you 'play the game,' acquiesce to the system for some personal benefit, safety  or security, and to what extent do you challenge and resist, so as to not perpetuate systems of oppression? I think Contra trys to make strong arguments on each side of the debate to demonstrate the tensions and competing outlooks through character conversations. Reducing it to 'Which viewpoint is Contra endorsing' is a little simplistic. I imagine she is more on the side of freedom of self expression and challenging gender essentialism and narrow gender presentation, but she probably sees the valid concerns of folks less on her side.

Justine portrays insecurity and the way society forces us to adapt to its norms and expectations, however, she makes insightful remarks about our modern day politics and the Machiavellian approach we might take to draw attention to a cause we believe in that challenges those norms, even if it comes at the expense of being honest with oneself. Tabby portrays brazen defiance and an unwillingness to compromise even an iota of what one is, and she believes much of what society thinks is merely an old heritage that should be reexamined and challenged, and that accommodating these norms, even for the sake of changing them, merely serves to perpetuate them and further marginalize people who don't fit into those norms through fault of their own. Neither is Natalie however. She doesn't give any simplistic answer, but clearly, her heart leans towards Tabby. Ater the Kavanaugh hearings, and the way the media just brushed off his anger and rudeness, a generosity they wouldn't have extended to his accuser had she acted the same way, and after Trump said that a female reporter never thinks and the response by the media was focused on the way the reporter handled herself gracefully, I cannot help but rethink about how complex the issue is. It is already difficult for cis women so I cannot imagine what it is that trans women face. Natalie is brave for portraying these two embattled extremes and the way she does it is brilliant because again, she doesn't offer any simplistic answer because any simplistic answer would be a betrayal to the immense complexity of this issue.

long time contra fan (first heard about her in 2016) here but i gotta critique this one tbh. (not some sort of harsh rebuke, just some suggestions and some observations/feelings i had during this video.)   i feel like this binary dichotomy of 'femme = assimilationist/gatekeeping = rational and charismatic' vs 'butch = radical = angry and violent' is way too simplistic. it erases loud femmes, angry femmes, counterculture femmes and at the same time kinda stigmatizes glamor in a way by associating it with more safe/conformist political views (when in fact high femmes have had a major role in radical trans activism for decades).   and as an anarchist Contra fan, I initially loved the Tabby character as a figure of good-nature ribbing between leftist sects (she's one of my favs), but at this point it's getting frustrating when even the centrist assimilationist lady is reading fucking judith butler for some reason, the nazi is a glamorous supervillain but the uncompromisingly anti-authoritarian and intersectional leftist just makes violent threats and hisses at people. the whole thing was structured like an 'own the libs' video kinda.   additionally, even the whole tv montage about the common threat or what have you zooms in scandalously on a 'mannish' trans women saying something threatening to a bigot before cutting to blaire white talking about how other trans people make her look bad. what's up with that? i thought tabby's speech about how it's valid to be a woman with a beard or a broad chest or etc etc was genuinely beautiful, and then the person discouraging her from promoting intersectionality is portrayed as the more reasonable and informed debater   some of the things said about butch and androgynous women & femmes in this video made me genuinely personally uncomfortable, as an autistic AMAB enby who's often felt dysphoria that people would perceive me as toxic masculine for being loud, interrupting people (often unintentionally) etc. coming from a very cis-passing, abled and 'Aryan'-looking trans woman, these sorts of fictionalized statements about 'you will never pass', 'society will always look down on you' etc do not feel like punching up or expressing sympathy when addressed towards butch and androgynous people.   in the end, i guess i just think that on a channel called ContraPoints that's dedicated to combating the right and taking away the stigma around socialism and gender studies, it doesn't make sense to spend *that* much time on making fun of antifa activists and queer anti-assimilationists for acting crazy and violent or w/e. meanwhile the nazi character is never portrayed as violent or threatening, even tho white supremacism is a leading cause of terrorism, beatings and homicides.   additionally, i wish that more of the content actually explored aesthetics and the lovable artist drag queen character, i was really looking forward to a video that be like introducing gender or decoding the alt right, but about the history of aesthetic philosophy with Plato and Kant and then the impact of modernism and postmodernism etc. in the end, i think this was a good premise for a video but it kinda got derailed. it just felt like a transcript of the exact kind of toxic twitter drama that lead me to quit most social media.

I think that the fundamental problem is not that optics supersede the authentic self. That we are in a circus rather than a forum is because our reality is warped by a reactionary narrative. To understand this we must first understand that we live in a nihilist society where tradition is upheld not in a reverence of the past but an acute sense of cynicism for the future.   The difference of something being 'aesthetic' or 'authentic' is that authentic things affect more than the subject in question. For something to be authentic, it has to be 'intrinsic' and maintain its forms regardless of circumstance. Something aesthetic is 'extrinsic' and will bend to suit the environment it is in. As a pretentious comparison: An famous painting and its replica.  The original doesn't only affect the artist and their audience. Any work ripples through culture and, regardless of its longevity, will leave an impact however small it may be.  A replica is devoid of this trace, it can't reproduce the impact the original had created simply because the original already exists. A photoshopped picture is one which had never been taken by a real camera and whose people on it never met in that instance. The replica will never be made from the exact brush strokes at the exact same time the original was.    If a cis man does all the things a trans woman would do he doesn't become a trans woman simply due to this 'ripple effect' being absent. A cis man will willingly change his behavior to whatever society sees as 'masculine'. A trans woman can't and must by definition be coerced. For something to be authentic it has to be felt even when it is there no longer. Same for a man straight that only sleeps with men.  So you may be wondering, what does this have with the reactionary narrative clouding our judgment? If something is new it is hard to see if it is real because it doesn't have a legacy upon which everything traditional rests. The reactionary right-wing answer is to assume the worst and reject every form of real change or progress. They mimic authenticity by pretending to be in touch with the past, calling on myths and legends which never happened. This is also the source of their incessant projection, they can't comprehend a world which is authentic in its own right. For them, only the optics of legacy exist. That's why they embrace aesthetic reason because it furthers their agenda. They can't be reasoned with because they never came to their conclusions through authentic reason.     As one of the comments already pointed out, if a doctor is a miracle healer but doesn't have a degree they are still a doctor. We shouldn't submit to this right-wing distortion rather we should assert our authenticity through collaboration and resistance of tradition so we can end this circus and build our forum on its ashes.   TLDR; Justine is counter-revolutionary. Go Taby! Smash!

There's been some criticism about this video.  As a transwoman not living full-time, I need to reexamine it.  I was, frankly really drunk upon my first viewing.  Note:  Google Chrome apparently doesn't like the word 'transwoman.'  Edit 1: I'm half way through the video, and it's obvious to me that you're playing Devil's Advocate, and Tabby is the real voice in the video.  Edit 2: I think most of the controversy is coming from well-intentioned cis-people who have no personal sort of perspective on the matter.  It's an idealized concept of transpeople.  I'm 6'2' (about 2 meters) and I am stocky even by male standards.  I have something of a baby face which has helped me to 'pass' now and then, but I work in fast food and I can barely afford my HRT let alone laser hair removal or surgery.  Perhaps this video was bound to be divisive, but there are realities to 'the aesthetic.' I am a woman, but my facial hair still grows, and without regular grooming, I'd have a beard.  I've been told my 'feminine' voice is good, but my default, comfortable voice, is fairly deep.  My breasts have grown since starting HRT, but they are hardly outside the realm of 'man-boobs' visually. I think this video is a realistic ode to the anxieties of being a transwoman, and wanting to be perceived as a woman.  In an idealized world, my identity should just be accepted for what it is.  In the real world, however, the waters get murky and my gender identity is partially negated by others' perception of me.  Every time I get gendered male, it brings me back to a dark place just a bit.  My only way to overcome that is by matching the 'Aesthetic.' Basically, I get the complaints, but even well-intentioned cis-people should keep their noses out to some extent.  They just don't get the context intrinsically.

While I understand why people might be upset over this video, I think it's a very important and necessary video.  Justine and Tabby are the voices I think so many trans women have inside of them, as least I know I do. Transitioning feels like this tightrope where you're always trying to balance your true self and the expectations society places on you. So many people won't recognize you as a woman unless you 'play the part' and 'dress the part' -- that's Justine's side. But fighting for women so that societies expectations become something more flexible is a noble thing to do -- we should all be able to be ourselves and that's Tabby's side. I don't think you're supposed to side with one or the other necessarily but hear them both out. And yes it's a sad video, but it's also a very true video -- a truth many of us are afraid to talk about but feel on a daily basis. I'm glad there was some honest discourse here.

I respect Natalie's work on Contrapoints. But I have to say, the video made me think that trans women define womanhood in ways that reflect their lack of experience with how being a biological female in this society profoundly shapes one's sense of self. One fundamental experience is being made to feel less human, less worthy, less everything than men in a million ways, big and small, from the moment you're born. Becoming aware of yourself as a sexual object during early adolescence, receiving advances from 30 and 40 year olds when you're 14 and clueless. Being made to think sex is something a girl gives up and a guy takes. Coming to terms with the fact that unintended pregnancy can ruin your life. It's about struggling to claim any voice, any space, in a male dominated world. Doing most of the mental and emotional labor if you're in a heterosexual relationship. I think I'm feeling all of this rather keenly, as are many women, in light of the fact that the U.S. Senate is about to confirm a lying sexual predator to the Supreme Court. That is, it ain't all aesthetics and performance.

actually, my comment from last week wasn't strong enough. here's my real feelings. and i say all of this with love, natalie. this is just as much directed at the comment section of this video as it is at you.  the problem is twofold:   1. you kinda end up claiming to speak for the trans community with this 'harsh truth' thing. that's not how i feel at all. i don't feel any more like a man than i did when i wasn't on testosterone, and i don't have days where i think i'm just fooling myself. this idea that we all have to 'face' that sends a really gross message about trans people as a whole, and this 'i guess we'll never know' middle-of-the-ground thing doesn't work when you're honestly just representing one side, and clearly favoring it as more 'real'.   you essentially end up implying tabby - and by extent, all of us who aren't internally monstrously transphobic - are just trying to 'comfort' ourselves. i like challenging media, i like difficult media, and i completely agree that all art is problematic. i like the videos where you're is open and honest about her struggles, the transphobia and rightwing, and the ending isn't always positive or comforting... but i don't like this fake horseshoe-theory bs where every argument is always in the middle of the road, no matter how terrible one of the sides is, and any art gets a pass because it's so Real and Challenging. it's not.  my problem with the video is the opposite - I think that the problem with this whole debate is that you are ignoring the scientific reasons behind the existence of trans people. Gender identity has biological basis.Therefore, a trans woman is different from a male crossdresser in the first place, because she has different brain development which leads to gender dysphoria. That affects her on many levels, including the motivation behind transitioning, the amount of inner insecurities, gender expression and behaviour. In my opinion this biological and neurological distinction makes her a woman. However, you cannot function as a woman socially unless you look like one in terms of your anatomy. It doesn't matter whether you are wearing high heels or lipstick or no makeup at all. As long as your body is perceived as a female body, you will experience misogyny. If not, you will experience misandry as a gender nonconforming AMAB person. That is why feminism is unable to protect trans people and expecially trans women from oppression, as it only focuses on misogyny while transfeminine individuals are not always perceived as cis women and experience misandry. Here is an example: a non-passing trans woman has to go through medical exams, because there is military conscription in her country. She is forced to run naked in the corridors of the medical institutions together with young men. All of them are denied basic privacy, because they are perceived as men. Doctors mock her for having long hair and nail polish, and she has to spend a few weeks in a mental institution to prove that she can't serve in the military due to being transgender. That humiliating procedure that exists in many countries of the world is pure misandry that feminism has no concern about (and we can't blame feminists for that, as they are fighting for women's rights, not men's). But who is going to protect that poor trans girl? Does the fact that she is suffering from male issues devalue her traumatic experience? Hardly. But it is time to acknowledge that we need to care about men's rights too when dealing with trans people for their own benefit.The experience of oppression that nonpassing trans women have is practically much more similar to what gender non-conforming AMAB people have to deal with.

I definitely like the video. It's very nuanced and I never really thought of a trans person 'being robbed of their identity' by simply calling them by a pronoun that they don't identify as. It's pretty much a culture-shock when you go for so long being referred to as a woman to have a snobby person refer to you as a man. I can't say I wholeheartedly understand the problem you face, but I can say that I definitely feel bad for you.  That said, the problem with this argument is simply that the definition of 'woman' is defined by society, too, instead of what genitalia a person has. I believe this is where majority of arguments fall flat because _forcing_ me to call someone a pronoun because they identify as what society identifies stereotypes as gender is akin to forcing me to say that white is blue on the grounds that _you_ said to. I feel like appending this exception to the first amendment to accommodate this is extremely complicated, and only really worth doing if the population of trans becomes way bigger, at which point it'd be more acceptable, maybe even courteous to call someone by what they want to be known as socially. I mean, we already do it with names.  I realize there are a lot of flaws with my argument, too. For example, just because a small portion of the population has an issue and the rest don't, doesn't make it any less of an issue, and it should still be addressed. I won't deny that it's super unfair to trans people to have to face this problem most likely every day, but I also won't deny that some change will eventually happen on it's own, completely naturally.

I'm delighted to see a video that looks at what radicalism could look like if aesthetic concerns superseded 'moral' ones.  Whereas Justine is the main mouthpiece for the idea in this video, and she's presented as wrong about plenty of things, it's not her prioritization of the aesthetic that's shown to be problematic but her narrow idea of what counts as aesthetically acceptable.  Tabby eventually gets her to budge on this by admitting that it's important to be yourself and imitating other people is 'a bad look'.  If all we had was the Tabby vs Justine argument I think we'd be left pretty stuck without an idea of how to proceed, because Justine's vision of what's a 'good look' is still so very other-driven and Tabby is still pretty gung-ho on the smashing, even as it doesn't serve her.  Meanwhile, as addressed, this debate taking place between two highly-passing, privileged women falls short of serving those outside that narrow category.  None of this is really solved aside from the provisional reconciliation they reach because they are both trying to survive. That's why I think the frame narrative with Tracy Mounts (sp?) is so brilliant and crucial here.  Remember that from the perspective of this particular video, Tabby and Justine aren't real, they're characters in a VHS tape.  Tracy is the host and essentially the center.  And who is Tracy?  'A lady who used to be a man dressed as a man dressed as a lady,' who is rocking some beautiful *peak* CAMP aesthetic and musing on the relationship between gender and color.  Tracy embodies the possibility of her own stand-alone *aesthetic of queerness*.   And why compare gender to color?  I don't think it's just because colors, like gender, are 'kinda based on science, kinda an illusion.'  Analogous color schemes run on a /spectrum/ and Complimentary color schemes are /binary/ (see what Contra did?) - but is any one more aesthetic than another?  No, both are crucial and beautiful.  But also it's not aesthetic to use any old color scheme in any old context - in color theory as in anything else 'context matters,' as do people's basic preferences for color, all of which are subject to change.  Meanwhile there are other kinds of color schemes (tertiary color schemes that have one of each primary or secondary color, split complimentary schemes that use a color and its compliment's two nearest neighbors but not its compliment), the existence of which would render a debate as to 'which is the best - analogous or complimentary?' silly. If gender is like color, then use of gender is an aesthetic thing that exists at the *intersection* of social expectations and unprompted individual self-expression.  Like color we can use it any way we think suits us, and yet we are always in a position to receive unsolicited (and almost always invalid) pushback over how we do.  I think Tracy/Contrapoints/Natalie is showing that we can paint with gender like an artist paints with color.  We can all be Gender Artists.

so.... maybe attempting to make this point about aesthetics in political discourse on the backs of (and at the expense of) non-binary &/or gender non-conforming &/or non-'passing' trans people wasn't the best idea? With your platform, and considering your relative privilege among trans people?

I understand these characters are not you, and that there are subtle narrative devices in place, so that 'this was a debate and Justine won because: better use of aesthetics (so, non-binary and/or non-passing trans people LDAR)' is not what you wanted viewers to take away from this. Your actual point, or actual question posed through this video, is very muddied and unclear though. In that way it feels like a huge contrast to your videos debunking fascist, 'alt-right,' and white supremacist propaganda. In those, you sometimes had a character representing a fashy point of view the but video made it pretty clear where *you* stand and no one would walk away from those videos feeling that they'd just been recruited into the 'alt-right' or that you, Contra, agree with the 'alt-right.' Justine's words were deeply invalidating to a wide range of trans people- all but those who are binary, *and* gender-conforming, *and* have accessed medical transition. And even for the narrow slice of trans people who 'pass as cis' extremely well, her words set up such a long list of issues to be self-conscious and insecure about- from how to move one's body, to how to react to assholes, etc, that anyone trying to follow her advice could easily develop Tiffany-Tumbles-levels of toxic (perhaps lethal) internalized oppression.  And all of it based in the quite possibly misguided premise that 'winning hearts and minds' of cis moderates through meticulous conformity & 'agreeableness' is the only and best way to achieve trans liberation. Nevermind that the Stonewall Rebellion didn't follow this formula, nor did many effective movements for social change. Arguably, buying-in to respectability actually harms movements like this (especially if It's an uncritical embrace of dominant norms to achieve a single-issue political end). It's very, very unfortunate that Tabby is presented as such an empty caricature of the Left that she can't offer a deeper, more historically grounded counter-argument to respectability politics. Another difference I strongly feel between this video, versus your brilliant past anti-'alt right' work, is that while I have never had to work/organize/regularly interact with someone who resembled your 'alt right' caricatures, I have definitely had to navigate interactions with many real-life Justines. I have had others within the trans community (1) assume I'm politically/strategically naive, (2) offer condescending 'advice' often focused on appearance (3) and actively try to invalidate and exclude me from political work because I am either/both non-binary and a leftist. Honestly, if any of them watched this video, I don't think they'd understand the subtle twists. I think they'd feel validated, like you agreed with them. I hope in the future your videos can return to the rhetorical clarity they once had. I also hope you'll consider listing trans-affirming suicide prevention resources on any video that has anti-trans content, repeats or examines anti-trans tropes, etc. It's rough out here and this video definitely sent some community members spiraling. Least you could do.

I agree with the implication of the romantic take on aesthetics near the end of the video - aesthetics doesn't HAVE to be false. We're used to thinking of aesthetics as the 'false front', the mask, the marketing, the propaganda. But that's only when aesthetics is being used to dominate and control. All aesthetics is is appearance, and the reality of appearance varies by context.  Human beings, all human beings, are corrupt. Which means that our aesthetics are never pure, never devoid of falsity. ALWAYS a performance. Even the 'sophisticated nihilist' who supposedly is beyond all mortal concerns has to perform in order to be socially *viewed* as a sophisticated nihilist.  I've spent a reasonable amount of my life not performing in society, and the outcome of this is that I was incomprehensible to other people. People understand others ONLY through performance - the absence of performance is the absence of identity. Not personal, private identity, perhaps, but public identity.  People refuse, absolutely refuse, to experience something incomprehensible. They became upset when I did not perform an identity, and when I continued to not perform they would invent my identity and then subject me to that identity.  Here's what I think this comes down to - people feel that they *have* to perform in society in order not just to gain power within society, but simply to exist in society. But they also feel on some level that something is lost, that a kind of innocence, a kind of pureness, of simply BEING, is being destroyed BY THEM.  Only by everyone SHARING in this destruction, only by ensuring that *everyone* performs, is the social crime of performance acceptable. Once some people stop performing, the feelings of guilt that the performers constantly feel start coming to the surface. But instead of self-reflection, the performers institute social and political controls on the non-performers, attempting to get them to conform to the culture of performance.  I disagree with Contrapoints's assertion that performance is necessary. If you're trying to gain power in the world performance is highly useful. If you're trying to be moral, to do what's right, and you believe that non-performing is moral and performing is immoral, then don't perform.  But Contrapoints is completely correct that society will make you pay for not performing. Society cannot abide it's own ignorance, and for a human being to not *help them out*, to not put themselves into an identity box FOR THEM to consume in easily digestible fashion, is, at least according to our society, a crime worthy of social censure, or worse.  For someone to not perform implies that society is the criminal, and that society's culture of performance is in need of censure. Needless to say, society does not simply roll over and accept this conclusion - it fights back, hurts and destroys whatever it feels it needs to to prevent coming to terms with itself.

I really related to the debate presented in this video, especially the part about gender being a performative effort. I came out as gay several years ago, and I thought that would once and for all  'correct' my inner homophobia, or at least redirect me to a more productive headspace, but it did not. Oftentimes I still feel like my old self years and years ago, so terrified of being 'found out' that I would consciously think of my movements, my gait, my voice; micromanaging every single perceivable trait so as to not get 'clocked.' I still struggle with that today, to the point where every interaction in the public space, especially with strangers, feels like I'm holding a cup filled to the brim with water that I must never spill while unicycling on a tightrope at the top of the Burj Khalifa. It has left me utterly devastated because even if I am technically out, I still engage in the performance of it all, and no single costume (for lack of a better word) feels right for me. It feels as if my internalized homophobia has left me permanently scarred, and that I must conform to what society perceives as acceptable in order for me to belong. But then, that violates my principles, and I feel as if that disposition invalidates why I came out in the first place. I don't have answers yet, and I doubt I will get them anytime soon. But I just want to say that this is a brilliant video, ContraPoints.

I think the solution might be something Natalie said as Justine in one of the earlier videos: being cool. Cool meaning appearing confident and in control of your emotions. By staying cool (while remaining approachable) you can make anything cool. Is it a kind of performance? Yes, but one that is used to express and make acceptable something unique and outside of prescribed norms - a synthesis of Tabby's drive for authenticity and Justine's knack for persuasion.   A great example is the character of Tyrion Lannister from Game of Thrones. Who would've thought a man with dwarfism could become a global icon of cool and sex appeal? Peter Dinklage made being a little person 'cool' through playing a character imbued with a deep, authentic charisma that embraces authenticity, collectedness, humor and vulnerability.  In the words of The Imp himself: 'Never forget what you are, the rest of the world will not. Wear it like armour and it can never be used to hurt you.' I think we transfolk (as well as other marginalised groups) can learn from that.

Coming from the medical point of view, patients must always indicate their genetic sex (male: XY; female: XX) and if they are transgendered and if they take any medications such as hormone therapy and if they have had any previous surgical procedures (sex change). Really nothing to do with how you are percieved, but with how you are going to be medically treated. You are still different from a 'cis-woman' biologically and so you will be treated differently medically (for your benefit and so as to not confuse the doctor and medical staff). So I believe it must be required to state your genetic sex in medical papers. However, what sex you choose on your email account creation is your business...  In medical school, posession of the Y chromosome means you're a male. Lack of Y chromosome means female. This also applies to those with genetic mutations with sex chromosomes. For example: Klinefelter syndrome, gene 47, XXY is considered a male. This is because of the presence of the SRY gene (among other things) on the Y chromosome.

Everything was always a spectacle. Every century was about the spectacle, it is only the form that has changed, not the fact that how you look is always 110% more important to the average person than what you're saying. The 19th century saw the rise of boxing, circuses, sports we know and love today, and advances in photography and later film allowed people to witness spectacle from increasingly exotic locations. The first people to fly weren't the Wright Brothers. A German immigrant named Gustave Whitehead beat them to manned flight. But the Wright Brothers had what he didn't - publicity and exposure. Debate in Athens used to be a kind of spectator sport, or similar to theater, it was making a stage play out of political issues of the time. The current year is not that different. While I appreciate the artistic style and the humor, and I recognize that the scope of this debate is within feminist conceptions of gender (gender as an internally experienced identity vs gender as an externally performed social role), I do not like the presentation of these two schools of thought as if they were the only viable views on gender. In fact, I'd argue that neither one is satisfactory in its own right:  If transgender feminism is correct and gender is an internally experienced identity, then what exactly does it 'feel' like to be a man/woman? Why is it that cis men and women are genuinely puzzled when it's suggested that it 'feels' a certain way to be a man/woman? And why is it that the only examples people seem to be able to point to of what it 'feels like' to be a man/woman are sexual experiences (i.e. what it's like to have sex as a man or as a woman), which are in fact attributable entirely to biological sex and not some subjectively experienced identity?  If queer feminism is correct and gender is an externally performed social role, then it's not at all clear that gender categories like 'man'/'woman' , 'boy'/'girl', 'him'/'her', etc. actually refer to what people mean by these terms. Ludwig Wittgenstein was correct in defining meaning as use - whatever we use a certain word to mean, that's what that word means. If we use 'man' to mean 'male adult human' (which is what most people do mean by the word, and the way it's typically understood), and queer feminism says that 'man' actually means 'person who performs the gender role typically associated with males', then queer feminism is mistaken (until such a time as we actually DO use gender designations that way). By the way, Wittgenstein was also correct in saying that you can't have your own private language - that's exactly what we're seeing with people who use this definition of gender, as they quickly get everybody confused and everybody starts talking past one another because they're playing incompatible language-games.  Neither of these theories of gender is satisfactory. In fact, the reason why they're not satisfactory is probably because they run parallel to the nature vs nurture debate (gender as an internal identity = gender is all nature; gender as an externally performed social role = gender is all nurture). Well, guess what? It's always both nature and nurture, and gender will undoubtedly prove no different.   I know Contra has done a video on gender in the past where she narrowed down all the viable theories of gender to feminist theories, but that doesn't mean those arguments are settled, and it doesn't entitle you to ignore all non-feminist perspectives on gender. Just because you stipulate that 'gender' is distinct from 'biological sex' does not mean that the words we typically think of as constituting gender actually ARE distinct from biological sex. Just because you establish a stipulative definition of 'gender' that you use in an academic context does not mean you get to impose that definition and pretend it's actually the lexical definition. These are all invalid moves, and it's not the way to have a discussion. (But if it's all politics anyway and politics is just aesthetics, then I guess it's valid. Well, it's not as if policies have actual real-world consequences and should be rationally determined in such a way that makes people in society better off, right?)

Amazing video, as always. That thing about 'being robbed of your gender' was spot on.  I think the best way to understand that is seeing trans people early in their transitions as teenagers during puberty (it's kind of what it is, a second puberty). Like, try misgendering an insecure young girl or boy, then see if they don't feel like shit and hate you forever.  For example, I am an heterosexual cis man, and I'm now pretty ok with my masculinity (I am 22, I have a massive beard, an high forehead, and get often mistaken for an older man in a somewhat neutral to positive way, so...), but I remember, when I was in middle school once I got misgendered by an old woman in front of my classroom just because I had long hair, no beard, and I'm very short. I assure you I wasn't at all feminine, and it was kind of a ridiculous situation, but it still felt like shit. When I said to her I was male, she was embarrassed and told me to cut my hair, my class laughed, and I hated her. I got over it in a few weeks.  If a person keeps getting misgendered into adulthood (thing that is very unusual for cis people, so it seems weird to them), they can either continue feeling like shit, become angry and bitter (see incel/trans parallel in Contrapoints' earlier video), or toughen up and don't give a fuck anymore, but it's still a shitty thing to do.  Cis people think it's not a big deal, but try being misgendered over and over, and over, and over again during a dinner or public meeting of sort, then tell me if it isn't irritating as fuck.  It makes you snap at a certain point. Also, if you're confident with your gender (like most adult cis people are), it's only irritating, but if you're not (like most trans people), it's soul-crushing.  In fact, it wouldn't be a problem to be 'less of a man', or 'less of a woman', if that didn't implicitly mean 'less of a person', and 'lesser' in absolute terms. So if you are in a situation where you just can't take it, it's not 'robbing you of your gender', but 'robbing you of your humanity'.  And I do not intend this in a 'monstrous unspeakable thing' sense, like torture and the like: every one of us experiences little moments of humiliation and dehumanization sometimes, without even realizing that. It's not uncommon, but it's still shit, and if you know with relative confidence that something is likely to have that effect, you could stop, just for common courtesy. Anyways... that was my rant to 'normies' (I kind of hate that word). Thanks for the patience. Feel free to quote me in any discussion you will happen to have with oblivious cis people on the matter, if you feel you're out of arguments to explain yourself :)  (what? I'm modest! I only asked strangers on the internet to quote me in their discussions, what's the big deal?! Everybody does it, jeez... XD)

I think... I'm really going to have to disagree with you on this one, which doesn't happen that often. I don't think you can equate a job with gender identity, I think however you identify and in whichever ways you express femininity is an entirely psychological and personal experience, while a job you perform is extremely impersonal and I would say it's something the average person rarely if ever actually cares about on a personal level. Losing your job isn't terrifying because you can't do that job anymore, it's terrifying because you need a way to support yourself. One individual job isn't important. Being misgendered isn't terrifying because I won't be able to buy food otherwise, it's terrifying because I'm having that gender taken away from me, and that _is_ intrinsically personally important.   Additionally, I would argue that gender is _not_ purely a practical and social identity, it's just as much of a personal one. I don't understand how you can previously state that you 'can't sleep without a bra on, because you must feel something on your chest', and then state that your gender is only relevant when it comes to how people treat you. Sleeping with a bra on doesn't strike me at all as part of your unquenchable and slightly terrifying thirst for validation, but I also believe that it's more than just a 'daydream' you're having (stating that the experiences and struggles of pre-transition transwomen are 'daydreams' is disgusting, by the way. Do you also really not understand that transwomen don't like to be equated to drag queens? Under like, any circumstances?). That's part of a genuine and personal experience that you are experiencing alone, regardless of social judgement.   I really agree with Tabby when she says 'All your advice is just to turn me into you', because that's what it is. Natalie says 'My way is the right way, why aren't you all doing it my way?' Then you actually go out of your way to cause harm to people like Tabby who express it in their own way, which I personally recognise as perfectly valid aswell. I don't care if some transwomen wear cat ears and want to smash things, that's who they are. I feel content allowing them to live their lives without hunting them down and telling them they're not real women unless they wear dresses. It strikes me as, frankly, an extremely self-important and masculine worldview.  I feel that Natalie's worldview comes from a place of autocratic practicality, and of panic. She seems to have this desire to strategize the world's population of transwomen into a singular identity to forward some vague goal, but I would argue that there is always room for interpretation, thought, and discussion, in any community. I think transwomen with broad shoulders, bald heads, cat ears, and those who wear combat boots, should be welcomed as women just as much as the passing bourgeois. I also think they have just as much of a right to call themselves women. I think you're going to have to accept that some people just express their femininity differently to you, and I just don't understand how the trans community functions when the dominant mindset is that there is only a single brand of womanhood and that we all must follow, or get out. Am I so incredibly ostracised seriously just because I love people for who they are rather than telling them they're _being themselves incorrectly_ and telling them who they should be?  Furthermore, concerning strategization of the population, I just don't understand what the goal could possibly be. You won't 'win' politics, if that's what you want, the struggle between progressivism and conservatism will always exist. What could you possibly hope to gain by eliminating different interpretations of femininity and uniting transwomen under your singular ideal of womanhood? I don't really want to become an autocratic soldier, dedicated to the unflinching will of Natalie Wynn, so I guess I'm not welcome here. It scares me that this mindset is the dominant mindset in transwomen, because I don't feel safe around them. I don't really want to be hunted down and attacked because I don't resemble a 1950s housewife. That's just not my idea of femininity, but I guess according to Natalie that makes me the anti-christ. Yeah, I know she'd sarcastically say 'That must be so hard for you' or some such, and I know I'm not a starving African child or a disabled woman of colour living in the American ghettos, but that doesn't make my suffering literally completely irrelevant. It just strikes me as Natalie cherry picking the struggles that support her worldview while downplaying the struggles of those who disagree with her by resorting to insulting her opponent's privilege... much like TERFs love to do.  Lastly, it depresses me to even bring it up, but did you really reference _Nietzsche_ of all people? You have to 'become yourself'? I thought we were beyond this edgy teenager's infuriating idea of 'philosophy', but apparently we're still rolling around in the pile of cum Nietzsche left from masturbating to himself and declaring himself the single greatest human being who will ever exist. The guy who caught the flu one time and declared that none will ever experience suffering the way he did. The rich white German guy who couldn't get laid, and so wrote an entire thesis about how it's because he's _too_ amazing. The guy who equated himself with a holy prophet, and said the only reason people ever refute his ideas is because they're too scared to admit he's right. In fact, that strikes me as familiar; Natalie, people like Tabby aren't refusing your idea of femininity because they're 'scared of the truth' or whatever edgy, childish idea you think, they're refusing because it's not _their_ idea of femininity. It's almost as if people are individuals with their own experiences, thoughts, and feelings. Similarly, there is no amorphous entity known as 'men' who judge your womanhood, 'men' are also individuals who have different ideas of femininity, too. One man might deem you extremely feminine, while another might deem you as seeming fake, and liken you to a drag queen. Even what _you_ see as feminine doesn't appear to me as particularly feminine, for example. It's more psychological to me, rather than physical. ~It's what's on the inside, my dudette.~   I'm not even saying that your interpretation of femininity is incorrect and that you should conform to mine, which is what you seem to be saying, I'm just saying there are different interpretations out there, and that even those who judge your femininity have different interpretations, so it's literally impossible to force the entire population of transwomen to conform to society's idea of 'femininity', because I don't really think there is one. If you look at Hollywood recently, apparently 'femininity' is the act of wearing combat boots and killing people, and... I still see that as a valid expression of femininity. If that's the kind of woman you want to be, I don't really see why you shouldn't be allowed to pursue that. You'd probably be much more interesting to talk to than whatever embodiment of traditional 'womanhood' Natalie wants you to be.  It just hurts that I'm hated by the society I live in because I don't conform to my given gender, so I turn to the trans community, who then hate me because I don't conform enough to their ideal of what my preferred gender is. Now I'm in the kind of mood where I don't really know why I'm alive, but I guess Natalie would say my entire experience and everything I feel is completely irrelevant because there are people who are suffering more. That's what I get for thinking I might have finally found the one person on Earth whose views on gender I actually agree with, but I guess there's just no place for me in any form of politics.

I'm a science teacher and the one principle I try to teach my students, above all else, is never stop seeking knowledge. I try to follow the same rule (after all, hypocrisy is the fastest way to lose one's legitimacy) and as such I have sought many 'Social Justice' channels in an attempt to understand the various perspectives found in the realm intersectionality. Some channels are extremely antagonistic, assuming the audience is either here to reinforce their already-held beliefs, or they are here to antagonize and insult the channel/creator/viewers. You are clearly intelligent, but you don't wield that as a club against the uninformed/misinformed. I admire that. Ironically, this attitude is the very thing that causes people to become immovable in their arguments and perspectives. The willingness to 'give-and-take' in a discussion is a mark of genuine intellectual honesty. Another rare and admirable trait.   Suffice it to say I have really enjoyed your videos, both in presentation and content. Thank you for offering a hand in cooperation to those who simply want to better understand others, not fight or troll. It is the only way we'll ever attain the goal of an accepting, compassionate, egalitarian society where all are welcome, because all are human and deserve a safe, peaceful existence.

Performing gender has always been very...back and forth with me personally.  I was sexually abused as a kid, and I hid myself under masculine clothing for a long time afterwards because I felt safer. Like I couldn't be a target because I wasn't presenting as feminine, and thus weaker. I cut my hair super short, I wore baggy pants and hoodies, and I never wore makeup. And that didn't make me appealing, and thus I was shunned for it.  Flash forward ten years, and I finally feel comfortable enough with myself to start wearing skirts and growing my hair out and I was in *tears* the first time I put on a long skirt again because it felt so RIGHT and it made me so happy that I could feel comfortable with that again and I felt like I had reclaimed that for myself, because I always loved pink and princesses and all that girly shit, but I finally felt strong enough to let it all out without feeling like I could be weaker for it.  Which opened up a whole new can of worms when I realized I don't really identify as female. I still love to present as feminine, but that always felt... *wrong* in the face of androgyny being the preferred presentation for non-binary, agender people like myself. Doubly so because I'm a chubby bitch and I got a soft bod with what could be called 'feminine' curves. (That I also took years to love and accept and regain my own self-confidence, but that's another story.)  I seem 'too feminine' to be non-binary, and I still struggle with that to this day, especially because I'm AFAB. It feels like cheating sometimes. Like I'm cis passing, and I don't want to take hormones or anything, I just identify as agender, and like to be feminine but it feels like I can't do that because then I'm not androgynous enough for the queers and just butch enough to be hated by the cishets for stepping out of the Girl Box because I don't feel the need to shave my legs or perform femininity for the sake of pleasing cishet bro boners.  I guess that's why I lean so heavily into ultra-feminine stuff like Lolita fashion, because it's feminine for the sake of being feminine, and not for the performative pleasure of dudes (though y'all know that cishet dudes will pop a boner at a slight breeze, so damned if I do and damned if I don't I suppose).  At this point I'm just like 'fuck it, I'll do what I want'.  Also, I missed my glorious queen (in a cat way, not in a monarchy way) Tabby.

I feel this is weakened by having Tabby refer not to a materialist account of the enforcement of gender but an extremely liberal model of 'inner truth' and free floating identity. It's especially odd since you have Tabby say the other character (I forget her name) can't account for where trans subjectivity comes from, but leaves herself open to the very same critique of her appeal to 'identity'. Perhaps it serves the needs of the skit, but it kind of limits it to a false dichotomy: a shallow liberal feminism against a shallow reading of Butler. And sure, that's pretty much the state of the 'trans discourse' right now, but let's point beyond it?  To state the point briefly, trans women are made women by the kinds of violence we are subject to, and the kinds of labour we are relegated to perform. That doesn't provide an etiology of transness (and I don't want one) but does point to the functioning of the logic of transmisogyny as a kind of regulatory violence, release valve for the tensions of gendered society, and means to produce a class of abject, disposable people. Though the monstrous figure of the trans woman as horrifying false woman/failed man drives this, it does not exclusively affect out trans women, and can hit us long before we reach the point of articulating womanhood or nonbinariness in our own terms.  You sneer at the 'Tumblr hugbox' in this video, which is a shame, because the debates on that platform - often quite vicious - have gone a long way to hammering out something resembling an adequate theory.  These theoretical points aside, I think the odd thing about the role of Tabby here is that she's clearly very concerned with aesthetics. She wears cat ears! She's playing to an aesthetic norm just as much as the other character, it's just not the norm of talk shows. So her arguments of not caring about aesthetics, and just being true to herself, ring rather hollow.  The biggest limitation, though, is that when Tabby is challenged on referring to oppressive dynamics that don't apply to her, no effort is made by either party to engage with the exclusion from the conversation of anyone but two thin white women. Like, that's part of the limitation of the format I guess, you can only show characters you can perform yourself, but the problem is not 'should white women try to be more respectable' but how to combat the mechanisms that make this a white women's conversation! And the problem with the 'use your privilege' argument taken to mean 'play the part of a presentable middle class white woman on tv' is that we're not just trying to secure liberation for presentable middle class white women, and this is at best all this tactic can achieve. Yes, pay attention to optics, but that doesn't mean regurgitating uncritically the limited narratives we're permitted to present.  Which is to say, it's all spectacle etc. The narratives of trans women on TV are far more in the hands of the producer looking for ratings, and without an enormous amount of care that most of us aren't capable of, it's better to refuse the stage than agree to a rigged 'debate' on whether we deserve to exist (which is to say, on how miserable our existence should be). Should we take the advice, and present respectably, not rise to provocation, etc., we are at the mercy of the other horn of the dilemma: we are caricatures of womanhood etc., or at best get gish galloped into irrelevance. This video makes out, at least in one of the 'contraposed points' (:p), that the problem is insufficiently respectable trans women, not the system that works to centre images of trans women as a chimera of pathetic faggots/violent monsters.  Basically, it is absurd to imagine that all the cause of trans liberation needs is more beautiful white women public figures, and that the only alternative is to performatively threaten people with violence. Neither image will 'work'. Our liberation will not be won in TV debates or through the right public figures.  And ok, that's enough for a comment that is unlikely to be read by anyone...
