Gender is an identity, sex is not. Sex is physical, you can reproduce with a womb, and a female egg, and this requires a male to do so, this is important - this is how the sexes are defined literally behind the many coloured glasses that we have. And no amount of abuse or psychological reconditioning can undo this, it is reality. The only solution is that since the sexes are physically definitive, as in we can technically break down the bodily differences that include even all of the information in the sex differentiated chromosomes, that the body can be fully changed. The problem for transgendered women is two; one that many transgender women merely identify as a woman, hence they do not want sex reassignment surgery. The second is that true sex change does not yet exist. Those who change sex do not have true female genitals, wombs do not exist for this process yet, they will never be able to give birth until this is a reality. And their chromosomes have not changed.  Though it is arguable whether changing chromosomes is truly so important to the process, you may be able to have all the sex characteristics of the opposite gender, working genitals, hormone therapy, etc, without really touching on any of the male or female chromosomes. Though,  that word again, even changing entire chromosomes is not unrealistic. We're getting pretty good at changing the genes of living things. How long do you think that would take to become a reality for us? I'm optimistic. And call me shallow, but the riddle of human mortality was more important to me that getting a more legit vaginal implant.  Why would I be affected by my sex so much if I knew that time is the only thing working against me? I'd rather spend my time thinking of how to live for a few more hundred years, or even more arrogantly, a lot longer than that. If you can do that, all your dreams follow. You will have all the time in the world to completely change sex. It will be an age where our physical differences are choices, superficial, being male, or female, will become blurry, and less meaningful. You can be anything that you desire, you can reproduce any way, with better results than natural selection could ever give you.  What happens then? Will people freely swap their sex in their hundreds of year lives to explore all reality has to offer? Will being a woman, or a man, become merely a phase in their long life? These things put into question our values toward these ideals.

'I can identify as a doctor and go around handing out diagnoses, but if no one recognizes me as a doctor then I'm not really practicing medicine, am I?',   So...I realize this is pretty much a throwaway line used for rhetorical effect, but it's a bit troubling to me because it reinforces the misconception of (Western) medical practice as an exclusively professional domain - which is not only ahistorical, but erases the lived experience and labour of many chronic patients.  This reframing of medicine, which has largely taken place over the last 200-300 years, neglects the integral and often cooperative roles that have been played by empiric, magico-religious, community and self-healers since the Middle Ages - to the point that patients engaging with practices of self-medicine within digital contexts are regularly represented as an entirely new phenomenon, rather than part of a continuous history of medicine as a system of diverse and loosely integrated practices.   Conversely, medical historians and postmodern philosophers of medicine - when they bother to address patient roles at all - tend to approach patients since modernity as passive objects lacking entirely in agency since 'their self-perceptions are themselves medically contaminated' - but again, this is inaccurate because it ignores the widespread and largely invisible labour of self-medicine that has always been a crucial part of chronic patienthood. (I think it's also worth considering how defining medicine-in-practice in professional terms erases its inherently social and interactional nature - regardless of whether they engage in community- or self-diagnosis and treatment, patients are nonethless practitioners of medicine.)   Sorry - this feels like kind of a trivial nitpick, but given the nebulous nature of this dialogue and the ways in which disabled perspectives are often rendered invisible in a lot of leftist discourse and philosophy, it feels important to me to call attention to the fact that practices of medicine are similarly not nearly as cut-and-dried as they're often represented, and as they seem to be represented here.

i am a cis lesbian and this a video that seems pretty intracommunity, but i want to say that, at least for me, i think womanhood is a trap for everyone involved. the efforts required to be 'successfully' feminine are beyond me. i can see every day what other women are doing that i am not, and it looks effortless and alluring and often attractive, and i'm torn between being happy for them and this yearning to perform femininity to that extent. i'm definitely not gnc, but i feel as though i'm failing to be 'good' at being feminine. there are certain feminine trappings for every kind of style from the ultra femme glam makeup efforts to the 'i rolled out of bed with sweatpants' and i don't feel as though i fit into any of them well. i just feel fat and ugly and although i would like to be more 'successfully' feminine, focusing on my features long enough to put on makeup or try on close just makes me hate myself even more and feeds my dysmorphia. it's a constant thing i deal with and while i do feel as though i'm a woman, i don't fit comfortable in nonbinary conceptions of identity, and i'm definitely not a trans guy, i just... feel like a failed woman. and i feel like it all the time. i don't know if it's relevant but it's true, and i think it's the result of womanhood as a social category emphasizing the aesthetics of women's appearances. it's a struggle every day.

Days later (not years)/MGK responds with his *best put together song ever*, Rap Devil. I've been subscribed to Contrapoints for some years now, and I think it might be one of the first time I regretted watching a video. Of course, it might just be the specific headspace I've been in these past few days, but that video left me rather... well, I suppose sad, but not exactly so. Now, the video was very well produced and a good dialogue for the most part. However, the overall tone feels a lot more melancholic than Natalie's other videos. There seems to be an air of resignation which lingers over the entire thing. Tabby is presented as being the sole representative of a community which is otherwise non-existent while Justine, who has by far the more pessimistic view, is presented as being mostly overwhelming and omnipresent. It feels as though the result is a dichotomy between martyrdom and self-erasure where middle-ground or change isn't achievable. I also find it difficult to accept Justine's point of view as tolerable when it, according to Tabby, involves her mocking Tabby behind her back. Adopting a socially friendly appearance and demeanor is one thing but using marginalized people as a way to prompt yourself up is just downright awful.  These issues are only compounded by the sour ending of the conversation where the two of them watch what I take to be a representation of the current climate, at least the one on the internet. I do agree that it is bad, but to focus solely on the Justine side of the issue makes the situation look absolutely hopeless. It seemed as though the final message was that things are terrible and they will always be terrible and the only way out is to adopt a veneer of conformity, that is if adopting said veneer is even possible.  Normally, I wouldn't mind a bitter video, but I fear that it might send a very negative message to questioning people, those early in their transition, and the non-passing people. And, I think that of anyone, these people aren't really in need a negative outlook given how they probably experience most of what is described here. Anyways, those were just my thoughts. I guess putting them on paper helped me some.

I think dissociating aesthetics from womanhood further proves the ambiguity of the identity, which further complicates the demand to be 'treated as a woman'.  In other words, if we go with Kitty's (is that her name?) idea, then we should accept her as a woman merely because that's what she wants, not because she performs in any way that is inherently womanly. In other words, the necessary and sufficient condition for womanhood is self-identification as such, in her view. But how does this fit into any sort of political demand for equal treatment of women, or an private demand of a particular individual to be more respectful to Kitty as a woman? Kitty will inevitably have different standards than Justine for what it means to be respected as a woman, no?  And if the point I'm making sounds like bullshit because 'it shouldn't be that hard, Jordan, to just respect a woman', then I feel like you're indirectly RELYING on aesthetics to make your case. The only way it could be obvious to me is if I rely on some intuitive sense of what is universally womanly. Where could such a sense come from if not an aesthetic vantage? Basically, I don't think we can escape aesthetics. I think the reliance on the idea of womanhood is a placeholder for a more sophisticated strata of identification, and that eventually there will be a normalized sense of experimentation, self-exploration, and self-discovery, that will allow room for somebody like Kitty to transcend the need for 'womanhood' and own a more specialized, personalized term or set of terms for her identity, one that fits with her aesthetic. So, I'm saying that aesthetics are unavoidable, but that that is ultimately a great thing about humanity, and it is being taken advantage of by the perceived gender binary. This abuse forces people like Kitty to try to fit into the binary by relying on one of its two labels while also combating the binary by heralding self-identification. I don't know the way out of such a system, so I don't blame Kitty for inadvertently perpetuating it, but I'm not sure that her strategy is really what will liberate humanity. Did this make sense? Thoughts?

I understand the politics of passing are uncomfortable, and that Justine and Tabby are fallible characters, but it hurts to see a near defeatist POV prioritized while issues of monetary access and nonbinary folks are glossed over. I love Dr. Butler's work, but it also needs to be said that there are a host of other activists and academics who have conflicting theories on gender and performativity in particular. I know that Nat is focusing on trans women, and as a trans man a lot of this resonates, but even though this is presented as kind of ? a debate ? it feels like there's still some nuance that's missing. I disagree heartily with Justine, and don't think she's right, but the presentation makes it seem like Justine is ultimately right. I think she makes some good points about practicality, but passing shouldn't be the only priority, especially when we can focus on normalizing and accepting GNC folks, cis or trans.

I kind of get what you could be going for with this, but it came off as pretty alienating. There's an imbalance of respectability with the two characters and Justine seemed to say more overall. The point of accepting and then putting aside their differences was weak and felt too late.   I understand very well that one can't expect others to give a damn, and the only person that can change how others see you is yourself, but some trans folks have it much harder than being able to pass with a couple hours of makeup and dressing the right way. Some, no matter what they do, won't 'pass' without spending money (that they don't have, so can't spend), and even with surgeries some won't 'make it'.   Maybe this video will motivate some people to try harder and they'll see some positive results in their lives, but I've always felt the idea of being a 'Good Trans' is very insidious and harmful. I wouldn't blame anyone for learning to pass and leaving this struggle behind, but it's not an achievable goal for many of us.

Gotta be honest, I have several criticisms of this video. I know trans people have to try extremely hard to pass, but you shouldn't have to follow gender stereotypes to pass. I know society at large will be more accepting of trans people if they do, but fuck that. A person shouldn't have to adhere to gender roles to justify their identity. And if other people don't accept a person's identity, it's the people's fault, not the individual's presentation of their identity. Don't pander to people who are skeptical of a person's gender identity. Act however the fuck you want, and if people don't accept your identity, that's their problem, not yours. Somethings are more important than optics.

Sure this makes me socially shunned and I have never been able to keep a regular job - but living the lie, using up all of the little energy I have at my disposal acting like I am expected to just plunges me into depression over and over again. Conforming to me is prison of drainage and belonging to any kind of group has never been a thing for me. Perhaps I can only understand it on a theoretical level; I have never felt it or even felt the urge for it other than under the threat of violence (see grade school). I am done with it.  I understand that very few people is in a position where they can cut out both social functions and work in a traditional sense so, while I will most probably feel alienated from society all my life, forever battling the depression it imposes on you, I feel lucky in that I am privilegied enough to be able to live expressing this level of honesty right now. As a cis gendered woman, this video does make me realize the real privilege I live with. I've never been a tomboy - I've never gone out of my way to be masculine or pursue a stereotypically masculine profession. But I've rarely put any effort into being feminine either, aside from removing facial hair once a week or two. I hardly ever wear makeup, I don't like wearing skirts or dresses much, I don't own any leggings,  and I tend to wear neutral or masculine-ish clothes, some of which are hand-me-downs from my boyfriend, who favours athletic wear. And yet I can take for granted that my womanhood will be recognized - that I'm very unlikely to be mistaken for a man in person (thanks to XX chromosomes,  a pituitary gland and sex organs that did all the legwork without me having to worry about it much at all), or on paper for that matter (thanks to my obviously feminine name, given to me by my parents). And if someone calls me 'sir' on the phone because my voice might be a bit low, it's something I can just laugh off. I can afford not to worry about, view it as a threat, or feel a stab at my identity. All of that is the privilege of being a cis woman in society.  I'm glad to see videos like this. Although they're certainly not intended for my 'cis-y' benefit,  they make me realize how thin of a ledge a trans woman might feel like they're balancing on. I feel like Tabby should be right in a just world, but Justine knows the world is not just at all. As long as cisgender norms continue to dominate, a trans woman may feel compelled to not only perform womanhood, but to over-perform, to be The Woman, hoping to escape the fear that all the effort to transition will somehow be Sisyphean (cis-y-fee-in?). At least, that's as far as I can see. I cannot really know the true struggle of being trans, of transitioning, in a world largely hostile to such an existence, to such efforts.

There are two underlying factors that I believe are being neglected or glossed over in this discussion:  genetic advantage and socio-economic privilege.  Genetic makeup plays a big part in whether or not a person has attractive features (sure some aspects of attractiveness can be subjective, but let's be honest, there are definitely objective biological factors rooted in what we find attractive).  So if you win the genetic lottery--so to speak--and have features that are in line with what is considered aesthetically pleasing (tall, slim/skinny, pleasant facial structure, healthy, etc.) then you will have a much better chance of being judged favorably and accepted by society, regardless of what gender you identify/present as.  As for the economic factor, if you don't have the looks but you have wealth and privilege, you can use those resources to 'enhance' yourself in ways that help make up for whatever may be lacking.  Of course, if you have both a genetic and economic advantage, then you have the means to forge your way in society without question.  If you don't have that genetic or economic privilege, though, then you have a much more difficult time being accepted no matter what gender you consider yourself.  Most truly passable trans women were lucky enough to have a running start with the ideal genetic material, and thus would be considered aesthetically pleasing as male or female (just look at before and after photos).  Many of them also had the economic resources to not only follow through with an expensive transition process, but to also maintain their aesthetic on a constant basis.  But people will gloss over this truth and instead choose to promote the false ideal of 'you could have what I have, you just have to work for it'.  Well, many people don't have the naturally good looks, or the means to pay for expensive treatments and operations, or the never-ending supply of high-quality makeup needed to pull off a look at the level of what CP does in these videos.  It is disingenuous to have such lofty debates on aesthetics and gender perception in society without acknowledging the under-lying realities of certain biological and socio-economic privileges, of which most people have little-to-no control over.  FWIW: Despite this criticism, I thoroughly enjoyed the video and it addressed many points that have been bouncing around in my mind recently.

Those of us who seek acceptance, want to rewrite the rules that are excluding us, to challenge power and to lessen its ability to exclude marginalized people in the first place. Tabby might be missing something when she talks about being an icon. She's a character that represents an extreme viewpoint created by someone who is known for exploring multiple viewpoints. Anybody who doesn't agree with her exact viewpoints, anybody in the center or even slightly right of Tabby, who might find her off-putting, can get on board with her anger because her message is tempered by her existence as a fictional character and the other characters in the Contra Points cast.

I think an interesting point I'd like to add is that acceptance of trans people (but only if they pass), really serves to reinforce the gender binary. I've spent time on trans forums, and I personally feel that a lot of people who could arguably be genderfluid or non-conforming are overwhelming informed that the solution to all of their negative feelings is to transition. Only then can you join this community of people who have a set of extremely specific commonalities. Unfortunately this almost universally includes using depression/dysphoria/social anxiety as fodder for making friends. So if you end up feeling that you don't identify as a man or woman, you're faced with the choice of losing all of your friends: all of the suicide memes and universal encouragement toward one obvious answer.   What I'm trying to say here is that it really hurts us as a society to only accept genderqueer people who fully commit to represent the epitome of the gender they're transitioning to.

While this video is definitely more reflective of the transwomen community, the conflicting ideas of 'looking the part' and 'staying true to self' in aesthetics is applicable to most, if not all, walks of life.  I am a cis man, and the conflict of aesthetics is something I struggle with often.  I am an introvert, and I am more comfortable by myself or with a small group of friends than I am in large groups, unless alcohol is involved.  I hate attending job fairs and networking with professionals in my field because I have to pretend something I'm not.  Even if I were a prodigy in engineering, no one would take me seriously in a job fair if I came wearing a hoodie and sweatpants instead of a clean pressed suit.  I have to take the time to work on my appearance, else I don't get a job where I want.  The networking version of me is not a reflection of my true self, but I have to act in the way others want because that's what they will respond to.  I understand that my experiences are not as dramatic as those in the trans community, and I doubt I can imagine the severity of the conflicts regarding ones experience they face.  But this video really demonstrated that conflict in a way that resonated with my own personal issues, and I find that remarkable.  Very rarely do I find YouTube content that speaks directly to my emotional conflicts.  It certainly speaks to the remarkable writing and acting Contrapoints has in her videos when a conversation about shoes that is analogous to the struggles of the trans community can be also be a metaphor of a broader issue in the human condition, cis or trans, male or female, straight or queer, or whatever.

When the people I previously referred to as my family brought out the standard arguments against me, my first impulse was to bring out the standard counters. Every time I did that though, I was left wondering why. The main issue with the things they said wasn't that they were wrong, it was that they betrayed fundamental errors in thinking.  They said: I don't believe that people can show no signs and then suddenly wake up and say 'I want to be a girl'. I said: Signs are often invisible from the outside, and may not be properly interpreted even by the subject. The real problem: In their mind, what 'people' did was more significant than what I was doing. I either fit some narrative or I wasn't valid.  They said: What gives you the right to just decide what you are? You haven't earned your identity. I said: [something about the ridiculously high dose of estrogen I'm taking, administrative matters, body hair removal and so on] The real problem: They thought identity was something that trans people had to earn, and if you weren't willing to 'put in the effort' you weren't worth respecting.  They said: Biological sex is fixed. You can't just decide you disagree with it. I said: Actually, intersex people exist. The real problem: They were thinking that biological sex necessarily had anything to do with gender other than a strong statistical correlation, and that this principle was more important than actual people's lives and dignity.  Every time I gave the standard defense, I didn't actually change anything. I expanded their overly restrictive worldviews just slightly to fit myself into them, and every time I did something new I would have to do all of that over again. I was making things easier for myself in the short term, at the cost of legitimising and validating their views -- not only condemning myself to a performative relationship, but allowing them to feel better about disrespecting trans people who don't fit the mould quite as well as I do.  You can have a broad worldview and still be closed-minded. Attempting to broaden someone's mind is missing the mark -- the key is to give them a mindset where they want to broaden their own. To show them that understanding something doesn't have to be a prerequisite to respecting it. And the _only_ way to do that, is to be incomprehensible. To be civil to a reasonable extent, but have no regard for their preconceived notions. High risk, low success rate, and absolutely not worth it if you don't genuinely care about the subject (hence why I no longer refer to the above mentioned people as family), but it's the only thing that really works.

This was a surprisingly depressing video on the topic. Because the thing is, I don't want to have to 'perform' womanhood. The women I always felt most similar to were of the tomboyish variety... t-shirts and jeans, messy buns, sporty, etc. To think that they will always have that freedom to be seen and accepted as women by society regardless of what they do, where I'll always have to walk this thin line of being afraid that acting too stereotypically-guyish means that my entire womanhood can be invalidated... that is completely not fair. The only external displays of womanhood that I've really ever cared about dysphoria-wise are the physical-body-related ones and the societal-treatment ones. And that's unfortunately irreparable because, well, the puberty that I went through when I was 14 years old is over, and thus I can't go back and make my body cisnormative.  There are lots of us like this. And this exact dance between either having to perform femininity for society to make our body appear more conforming to their narrow gender norms, or just being ourselves and acting like we would have been acting had we been cis women but opening ourselves up to invalidation in the process... that is depressing. Damned if you do, damned if you don't... and all because of something we can't change which we never wanted to go through in the first place and which we've suffered tremendous anguish over not being able to correct.  I'm siding center-left toward Tabby's side. Surely something is fundamentally wrong and needs to change in a society where people are forced to do this, and where certain subsets of the community will NEVER have their voices taken seriously. (Although I do disagree with her on the smashing part.)

Ok but concept: Gender is a social construct. Social constructs are made by people, and they gradually shift with the actions of people. We are people, so really we can make or break any construct we want and that's how culture evolves  Plus, having gender being only a performance of an already existing construct and archetype? That's really hard on nonbinary people, who often don't have a cultural image of what they look like and how they act. Or they relate to an archetype that isn't considered a normal gender. The archetype of Ideal Man and Ideal Woman are just as non-existant and mythological as, say, the archetype of an elf -- which people were identifying as their gender back in those pre internet ages when LOTR hit the stage  Plus, if a person has a gender and there's no one around to perform it to or convince, does it still exist? Does it and all the feelings and perspectives go away? For most nb people I know, it doesn't.   Gender is less a performance, and more a way of relating to the world, a place you feel you occupy in the big tangled web of reality and ideas that make up culture.   Like the metaphorical little imperfections that turn a clear, uniform, homogeneous rock into a colored gem, gender is just a thing that colors us. Like a gemstone absorbs and reflects light, gender, and identity in general really, is how you absorb and reflect the world, and ideas, and things in general  And even though some people can't see certain colors, or any colors at all, and we can't see beyond our little range, those wavelengths are still things that do stuff, even when not being perceived by a passer-by

Honestly i feel like the way we should handle this very very fine dichotomy is to know who your audience is. When your audience is well-versed in trans issues, tabby's perspective of speaking up with radical ideas that are just fighting for freedom from how gender exists currently would actually work. However, around the ordinary, raised-transphobic person, it makes more sense to start with keeping them comfortable and slowly edge them into being more comfortable with trans people and the most basic and simplistic trans issues. Without aesthetic, it's difficult to even break through the smallest bit to the average transphobe, and usually causes them to have an even worse view of trans people. Theres nothing wrong with knowing your audience, if there is an audience you want to reach, and using aesthetic to keep them from pulling away.

I feel like both Tabby and Justine are correct simultaneously (which I think is the point of the video). Tabby is arguing about how the world SHOULD be, Justine is arguing about how the world IS. I am a Black cis intersex woman, so I experience aspects of this conflict on a few different facets.   Many, if not most, people of color practice code-switching, the act of changing one's speech and/or behavior in order to be more palatable to a white majority. Personally, I code switch in ways that temper my expression of emotions/behaviors that are stereotypes of Black women. For example, when I'm around non-Black people I don't express my anger as readily, I try not to be 'sassy' so I use a more subtle humor, I don't let my voice get too loud even in situations which would normally warrant it. And those are only some examples. But I am in Black-majority spaces so infrequently (I live in a majority-white city, go to a majority-white university, etc.) that I start to question whether this code-switching, which is a performance, has become so habitual that it is now a genuine part of who I am. Like, I used to be a pretty silly and expressive kid, and now I'm not. Did I just grow out of that naturally? Or did I realize that Black woman aren't supposed to be silly and expressive in order to be taken seriously, and I changed not just my behavior, but my personality itself? I would love to take Tabby's point of view and just say eff it to the majority and act however I want, but the sad reality is that when I take Justine's POV, my life is easier because the world accepts more just a bit more easily.   On the gender side of things, I probably think about my gender expression much more than most cis women because I am intersex. For context, I was raised as a woman, I identify as a woman, I am universally perceived as a woman, and I express myself within the boundaries of acceptable femininity (i.e I'm not the girliest girl but I don't shop in the men's section either). When I was growing up, I didn't consciously think about nor control my gender expression. I just did and wore what I wanted to, and I didn't think about it any deeper than that. But as I became more away of my intersex condition in my teen years, I began to question why I felt like a woman at all. After all, there are parts of my body that are not typically female, so that's not why. So is it because I was raised as a woman? Would I still identify as a woman if my parents had decided to raise me as a man? I mean, I intellectually understand that sex and gender are not the same and that they don't necessarily correlate (and obviously many cis non-intersex people understand and accept this too), but it's a whole other thing to have to deal with that difference on a personal, identity level. I even experience a mild form of gender dysphoria (I think. I'm using this term because I can't think of another one, but I don't want to misappropriate it so if there's another term for what I'm about to explain someone please tell me.) I really, really don't like the parts of my body that aren't female. They make me feel like less of a woman, even though I know that my sex has no bearing on my womanhood. I've even considered surgery. I'm trying to be all Intersex and Proud, but sometimes it's difficult, and I just want to be normal.   Anyway, this was a great video and I'm glad I found your channel. Hopefully all of my commentary is useful to at least one person.

Excellent video as always. The thing I can't seem to reconcile is this idea that gender expression is a blank slate drawn in by culture . While I'm by no means an intellectual, it would seem that biology plays a rather large role in behaviors and gender expression. Take children's preferences for violent stories being favored for young boys as an example (I apologize having no study to cite atm). I wouldn't think that animals develop a sense of gender via this proposed 'blank slate' like bower bird nest building. That to me seems to some extent instinctual. I feel like this whole gender debate has countless variables within it that make the definitions so hard to honestly define. Is hypergamy cultural or biological? Is this significant to gender expression? I can't believe that gender alone is a social construct, but I'd be equally dishonest to say it's completely biological either.  Take the fact that trans people have variations in brain biology from non trans people of their biological sex, and maybe in that sense they are biologically their desired gender. Both left and right approaches frustrate me, as the right flat out deny any sort of flexibility in gender as the result of culture, while the left claims it's completely defined by culture and not biology. It has to fall somewhere in the middle, which while extremely difficult to grasp, may make everyone actually reach a consensus on this issue.

I cannot speak for women. I mean, I can try but it's gonna have obvious inaccuracies. But I can relate to some of what was said. As a gay man who's (like many others) had to juggle many circles including the extra gay clubbing scene, the stuck up 'locker room type' boys who'll endlessly talk about vagina but if you mention penis they threaten your safety, and the many variations of how people expect gay men to be around them, I've definitely had to perform a lot and to learn what the most functional and adaptable me was, and then become that me. It's a daily exercise that I only ever get better at. But I always feel frustration. Frustration that anyone's expecting me to be something that's not accurately me. Frustration that I'm bending to them like a good little slut (which I am). Frustration that I don't really know what's the next thing I'll have to learn to be 'proper' gay.  Now, it's not all ugly and bad. I've learned to enjoy most of it, most of the learning. To become interested in what people think gay men are like. To have open arms when the next big trend of drag queens and gay performance will knock at my door.  But the frustration always comes back here and there, for major and minor details. And I definitely agree with the Cat girl, and I would love to smash the people who expect a lot out of me for ridiculous reasons. But I don't hate Natalie as depicted in this video. I'm not completely lost as to why she says what she says. And she's still right that I'm gonna end up performing my identity in conform ways, way more that I'd have expected in my college activist years. And I'm at peace with some of it, just like I had to learn to be at peace with saving money and doing sad sad work. And making plans that had to do with anything other than my own expectations, that was always a nightmare. Now, it's just the way to fit in society. I keep in mind that someone out there has ideas as valid as me and that disagreeing with them won't make me have the life I expect. We'll have to meet somewhere in the middle and understand that we can't just hate each other's expectations. We all have expectations, and we all end up performing accordingly. It's kind of a form of respect, really. It's messed up from a philosophical standpoint, but it works in real life and it feels really good to not fight itall your life.  College me would hate, love and pity my current self all at the same time. Just like I hate, love and pity my college self.

The dialogue format and the fact that you let arguments go to their logical endpoints without resorting to politically motivated distortions work really nicely. Finding arguments politically repulsive is no excuse not to give them any thought - our job as progressives is not necessarily to deny the factfulness of opposing talking points but to give them our own spin/narrative and disarm our opponents by showing that the facts don't really show what they think they show.  I know it wasn't the main thrust of this video but I found the stuff about the nature of gender interesting. I've never really found Butler's performativity theory convincing. It comes with a kind of a superficiality that I don't like and I think Tabby is right to point it out.  Gender seems to me to be contingent but not arbitrary. That is, there's some kind of inner determination (or 'inner truth' like Tabby would say) involved but ultimately it's impossible to 'prove' to be this or that gender. Marks of sex/gender, like behavioral traits, genitals or even chromosomes, only function as long as we don't interrogate them. Ben Shapiro can point to people's chromosomes as long as he wants but it's simply impossible for him to explain how having XY chrosomes makes him a 'man'. Why are these 'male chromosomes'?  Aaanyway, I hope there's a lot more to come. Your videos about trans issues are probably your best ones (no surprise there!). Even for me and I'm cis. The fact that you're passionate about these topics and struggle to make sense of them really shows - and transforms into quality content.

One of the realizations of living in a communal reality is that other members of reality can, to some extent, modify the reality as it relates to them.  If someone views you as crazy, then to that locality you *are* crazy.  If someone views you as a woman, a man, or otherwise, then they have enforced that reality in their locality.  When a larger group within communal reality does this, they have a larger effect by virtue of making up a larger part of that communal reality.  Likewise, if someone has a lot of social capital, whether that's the personal-to-you capital of a confidante or the communal capital of a public figure, then in their place of power do they also have great effect.  However, you must also recognize your own ability to have an effect on communal reality, and that your effect within your locality is also greater.  Rebuking those who have a toxic effect on the communal reality is its own kind of power.

What I like about these discusion videos is how I can empathize and agree to a certain extent with both characters. In Justine's case I think she is correct when it comes to being a cis-facing trans activist. (This is just a term that I made up, so I would define it as being an activist that is attempting to improve the Cis perspective on Trans people.) In this circumstance Justine is right, if you are making or participating in media who's primary audience is for Cis people then passing and being civil is extremely important. When fighting for the most basic rights of trans individuals it will be easier to pass favorable bills when the public perception of trans people is them being the pinnacle of masculinity or femininity. Now this will lead to poor stereotypes of trans people, one that will take a while to stamp out and bring the perception of trans individuals back to a more reasonable center. That being I think getting basic legal protection for trans individuals and changing the perspective away from the idea that people who are trans are simply pretending to be their gender is more important then the negative repercussions that will come from Justine's perspective. Tabby's perspective on the other hand is more important when looking at trans focused trans activists. (By this I mean activists are focused on making trans individuals and people who are experimenting with gender identity feel more comfortable and understood.) When looking at these activists Tabby is absolutely correct. Justine is presenting an unhealthy and untenable presentation of femininity, one that most people who are transitioning or are looking to transition will not be able to meet, at least not for a very long time. For these people its important to tell them that there isn't a right and wrong way to be trans, and they can express their gender how they see fit. A balance of activists like Justine and Tabby are needed in order to build a holistic and functioning trans community. (Wow that was longer then I intended, I am cis btw and this was just my perspective and my take away from Natalie's video. If you disagree with me please respond to this to let me know, I really appreciate feedback and different perspectives.)

To me I think this video perfectly highlights that often the problem within conversations about gender identity is that it ignores how the category of gender itself is the problem. The idea of performativity laid out by Judith Butler (who later when talking about how TERFs used that to bash Trans women said that 'one should feel free to explore the course of our gender identity') only gets us so far as how we can live our best lives in response to gender being put upon peoples bodies. We live within the confines of what gender is, but we need an insurrection against the very limits of its existence. Judith Butlers original point in creating 'Gender Trouble' was to outline how the idea that there is a 'Female' subject at the heart of feminism is the problem, because the 'Feminine' subject is always being reconstructued. There is no template to which one 'attempts' to mimic femininity (which is the point being made when Tabby asks where do you get your ideas of gender from'. What 'Femininity' is is determined by its juxtaposition to Masculine norms. Thus the very idea of 'gender' itself as a category that limits the characteristics of ones existence I believe is the problem. This is a super good video and I liked it a lot!

I found this video really powerful Justine. As a cis woman I obviously cannot relate to having the validity of my gender identity scrutinized on a daily basis, but in seeing the struggles of trans men and women close to me, and in my own experience as a woman with autism, the dichotomy of optics/aesthetic vs unchecked inner expression hit home. The philosophical question of whether the identity we perform for society is reality; or whether the identity of our personal 'truth' is reality; is something I struggle with. I don't intend to remove trans women from the topic of this discussion,  but I've realized that trans women and autistic women have similar experiences with that dichotomy of self-expression. There is also a disproportionate percentage of transgender and non-binary people within the autistic population so it wouldn't be too farfetched to note similarities.  Women on the spectrum can develop 'masking' as a survival mechanism wherein they observe neurotypical behavior and alter aspects of their own 'optics' to match. This is a very energy intensive task and in my case lead to depersonalization, dissociating, anxiety and depression. Some develop eating disorders. Experts believe masking causes women to go undiagnosed or misdiagnosed as BPD or bipolar (also common in transgender people).  Most experience extreme relief after diagnosis only to realize that gaining introspection doesn't free them from societal expectations. Masking isn't limited to women but is more common, I believe due to the limited range of how society perceives acceptable female behavior and appearance (like Tabby says). In professional and political settings (which are often one in the same) women, in general, need to do a lot more to be respected - makeup, gender-appropriate clothing, smiling and speaking delicately to not seem 'rude'.  The social mechanism is the same for autistic women and trans women but the outcomes are different - when autistic women don't conform, we are seen as rude, untidy, incompetent; when trans women don't conform they can be seen as all those things and also get misgendered.  In the end I don't really know which way is better (changing optics to fit society vs free inner expression) but perhaps the cynical answer is changing aesthetics of how society views trans and autistic people will validate these groups in the political conversation and thus lead to a better chance of society accepting a wider range of inner expressions.

Excellent video :) I just want to help clarify a part where you discuss 'gender performance'. Butler uses some pretty poor wording in Gender Trouble, so she's had to go out of her way to clarify what she means by this.  To my understanding: Gender Performance is exactly what it sounds like--literally acting out a caricature of what any given individual deems to be associated with the gender.  This is often done in theatrical and showy ways such as through drag. GENDER PERFORMATIVITY on the other hand is what Contra referred to as the 24/7 drag: it is how all human beings subconsciously act out their gender through what they say and what they think.  As a man, if I gravitate toward blues and blacks instead of yellows and pinks; this is not natural, but is instead me acting out the gender conditioning that my society has exposed me to.  For trans women, their gender performativity typically aligns more closely with whatever happens to be the opposite of their bio-sex (though this is not always necessarily the case).  Having a GENDER EXPRESSION that doesn't match your bio sex involves the acknowledgement of societal gender norms and twisting them, taking what any given society deems to be related to one gender and adopting them yourself (ei: choosing to wear a skirt means that my gender expression is female, even if I am a straight bio-sex male who identifies as male).It's all a lot to take in, but gender is complicated, so I've tried my best to understand it to the best of my ability.  If anyone thinks that I said anything inaccurate, please feel free to correct me, as I'm always excited to learn more about these topics. Peace.

I would imagine part of that identification comes with observing what standards our society attaches to women and men and identifying whether those standards align with your own identity. In that vein of thinking, it would be important that other people treat you like the gender that fits you best and many people have a hard time treating people as the gender they identify with unless that person conforms with society's standards of masculinity and feminity. This video bring up a very important duality, content x form. As the yin and yang, this duality is complementary instead of contradictory. One can not live without the other. You will not eat a cake that doesn't look/smell good, you will not approach someone with unfriendly body language, you will not notice a book without a good cover. But you also will not like a cake that looks/smells good, but tastes like crap, nor a person who seems friendly but treat you rudely, nor a book with great cover but bad story. It is easy to dismiss form as being shallow, but it is part of reality, the part that signals to the external world what might be inside. Form is not about hiding or enhancing content (although sometimes is used that way), but it is about comunicating it. I don't think we can combat the shallow uses of form (the meaningless stereotypes) by just rejecting it. We must embrace the importance of form, if we want to use it for display of real content, instead of just a facade. I, giving a simple example, don't care about clothes, but I dress fairly well, because I know other people will judge me. I don't dress exceptionally well, because that would be unauthentic with my personality. In the same way, in other instances we must find a balance between who we are and what we want to communicate with other people, taking in account that stereotypes are just inevitable. I know that things get complex when is about your gender identity, but, how complaining about things that you can't control improve your quality life? If I hate dressing well, how not dressing well improves my life? More often than not, life doesn't hold up for our standards of fairness. But I wonder if, once we, as a society, starts to understand and appreciate the importance of form related with its content, we could get rid off useless stereotypes, and hold to the more fair and humane ones.

What exactly is gender then?  It's easy to conceptualize masculine (cis)women, and it's easy to understand feminine transwomen. However, it's confusing when someone claims to be a transwoman, but presents themselves in a masculine way. In that case, what does the claim of womanhood even mean? We've already disconnected genitals, chromosomes, and other biological (and latent biological) traits we are born with. Femininity and masculinity, on terms of how one acts and presents oneself, seem like the only criteria left by which we define womanhood. As sympathetic as I am to a transwoman facing with an internal crisis like this, we need concepts people can wrap their heads around. Demanding unquestioning sympathy and acquiescence to the demands of the most radical transfolk about how they should be viewed is not a sustainable strategy for solving this dilemma.

I rather enjoyed the music -- especially the sort of spooky bits. Good job to whoever did that.  As for the notion of aesthetic and identity... I (a straight cis fella) feel like I could ramble on about how I don't like that mindset for a long time. But to keep it short, I find the pursuit of aesthetic and using it to define who you are to be pointless -- I see how it is a rather weighty matter for a trans person. But I'm thinking back to my high school and college days when I recall a lot of people who decided that what they looked like determined who they were to a far greater degree than what they _did_ and what they _believed._ Frauds, essentially. To me, that way of thinking seems like it leads to insanity, or (to be less hyperbolic) to dissatisfaction and a feeling of emptiness. We all have different struggles, and like it or not appearance matters since those of us who are sighted rely on appearance a great deal. But I've personally always preferred sincerity of character. Just BE who you are. Whether or not you look like a woman, _be_ a woman. Right? (Geez, it's soooo easy). The appearance will matter, but I find it matters less so than Who You Are At Your Core. And though I may be ridiculously wrong here, I suspect that transitioning isn't just about looking like a woman -- otherwise a person could simply stick with drag and perfect that illusion -- but feeling like one for your own peace of mind, so that even when you don't put in the work to dress up you still _know_ you're female despite lounging around in pajamas with messy hair and bingeing Netflix on the couch.  I really hope I didn't come off as patronizing, because that wasn't my intention at all.  Of course I also think that the clothes we were are irrelevant. Suits... how bizarre is it that suits are accepted to confer some notion of status? Or that a straw hat seems to detract it? It's all so completely arbitrary. If the entirety of the human race woke up tomorrow with complete amnesia about our cultures and wardrobes and everything else with no clues to remind us... what would that world look like a week later, or a year later?

Why bother catering to the armchair centrist  expectation that a disadvantaged group has to  be personally  responsible for their own acceptance? Isn't it more practical to approach social reform and acceptance as a block? Real life doesn't work like some tacky oscar bait film revolving around some 'magical minority'.  If we demanded every Black person have to prove themselves individually worthy of respect instead of passing legislation or advocation block social reform odds are there'd still be segregation and apartheid. He was skeptical of gaining anything other than easy allies, so why shouldn't we be? Why give in to society's demands that  we have to individually win over every alt-right edgelord omni-skeptic in a 10000000000% logic based debate when we can improve our station in society with allies that will actually fucking listen?

13:39 This is an important point that I think writers like Judith Butler misses in their writing (or at least had not adressed in the pieces I've read of her). By emphasizing the individualistic performativity of gender, they can be misread as essentially claiming that social roles are atomistic: that anyone can be anything if they truly believe so and perform it. What is missed is that gender, and all social roles, are not just the prerogative of the performer, but of the audience as well. Simply put, social roles are relational. Gender is relational. Race is relational. You can claim you are a woman (or a man) all day long, but if no one in your social surroundings accept that, then you are, for all intents and purposes, still the gender you were assigned at birth. This is what's called 'social reality', which more or less means that if everyone believes something, and act as if though it were true, then very often, it's impossible to challenge that notion, or even consider that it could be false. Just to be clear, I'm not making a value comment here - I'm not saying this is fair or good, or anything like that, but rather that emphasizing performativity without underscoring the crucial role played by audience acceptance is misleading and potentially sets people up to fail (or at least become very frustrated) by not including all the factors of the equation.   We live, for example, in a world were being 'trans-race' is essentially impossible, because, in short, it's part of the 'social reality' that race cannot be changed due to various ideas of what race *is* (ie. deeply materialistic/essentialistic and informed by long-standing power-inequalities that makes such a concept of transition either deeply offensive or outright laughable). I know it might come off as a false equivalence comparing this to changing genders/coming out as transgender, but it's the best analogy I could come up with that shows how we kinda arbitrarily decide what is considered possible and impossible within a cultural framework. Being transgender is of course considered equally impossible in a number of cultures, and no matter the performance would probably just be shot down as eccentrism or insanity. Or if you want to get into some less West-centric issues - consider the issue of changing castes in certain parts of India. That's socially impossible in many cases, no matter how much you change your profession, name, diet, worship practices and so on. In the eyes of many people, your caste is integral to your very physical body and spiritual self, it's a part of the dharmic cosmos, not something you can change.  To use a brutal example: even if you perform man-ness every day of your life, but no one accepts this as a valid performance, then you'll probably end up in a grave with the female birth name, and every historical record naming you as a woman and nothing else. The unreceived or rejected performance is often simply erased.  Now, it is of course possible to challenge social reality, which trans and gay people know a helluva lot more about than me (and I've probably veered too close to cis-splaining as it is, I hope not beyond), but it is hard. It takes time. And it is potentially very, very dangerous. Remembering to get the audience (ie. friends, family, coworkers, neighbors, wider society) along and accepting of the premise of the performance is, whether one likes it or not, crucial if one actually desires full range of expression and acceptance. How to do that is outside of what I know.

As beautifully dizzying as this was. It feels like your gender dysphoria is gerrymandering the definition of woman to allow yourself to identify as a one. If gender is how one performs one's sex then that implies that there is a correct way to perform it, when the way that we perceive gender is descriptive. If men started taking up art instead of sports then art would be the manly thing to do. I am a man therefore anything that I do is manly, as in I am doing it in a way that a man would. If I decide that I want to put on make-up, wear a dress, and suck a dick then descriptively I am doing it like a man because I am a man. I'll grant that masculinity and femininity exist objectively as can be measured by the white to gray matter ratio in the brain. But as far as pronouns go: they are quick approximations to refer to one's sex, if you are lucky enough you might imitate a woman well enough you might be approximated inaccurately. As a thought experiment to determine if pronouns refer to gender or sex I imagine if my 'male' brain were put into a female body what would I expect people to refer to me as? The answer seems obviously female, to expect anyone to guess that I have a masculine brain would be unfair and to ask someone to refer to me in accordance with how my brain is structured is asking them to break their internal  categorizing mechanisms for me which undermines why we have such faculties in the first place. Aesthetics is an interesting part of gender and misgendering. I'm a cis woman and I don't mind being misgendered online where people assume I'm male from my text, but find it hurtful to be misgendered in person.   Usually it's because the other person is intending insult, and you can write them off as being a dick, but I was once in the very confusing position where someone was genuinely trying to defend me while misgendering me. Myself  and a boy (let's call him Sam) at school where incredibly similar in height, hair type and hair length. I never wore the skirts that came with school uniform and everything else was the same. If together, we were often mistaken as siblings or even twins. It was something that amused us. The lad misgendering me meant well- one of his mates called me she and he was trying to defend me by pointing out 'Don't be a dick, he's obviously a guy.' While I knew he was actually defending Sam, and in some ways it was more mistaken identity than misgendering, I was too shocked and confused to speak up while he was listing off all my masculine features and convincing his friend I was Sam/a boy. Other than wearing trousers (which is more unisex now), I thought I looked 'pretty/feminine'. It didn't help when I finally pointed out I wasn't Sam that the lad was embarrassed and got defensive. It hurt and made me put a lot of effort into separating myself from Sam through hairstyle, makeup, wearing skirts and tights. Honestly I hated it and the compliments I got after were strange double edged things that felt like they were rewarding a lie. That I only got to be 'a girl' if I put effort into it. I couldn't just 'be' a girl by virtue of being one. I didn't get to be recognised as my gender unless I played by their rules.  And yet, I don't mind people misgendering me by text- by my words and personality alone. I've even been told 'No, I don't believe you, you type like a guy' when trying to correct someone. That just baffled me more than insulted me. Sometimes I'm even happy leaving the assumption because it's easier being a guy online. Yet having someone see my, in person, and go 'you look male' hurts.

The burger you make for yourself tastes ten times better than the one from the fast food chain, but you can't spend millions of dollars on commercials that convince everyone that this is true. I'm a Cis, straight, white male and realize that I was born on a mountain of privilege.  That being said, I never thought of my gender as performative.  Even when I was little I remember really disliking what I felt was expected of me as a man.  I grew up in the rural Midwest to a father who had very clear expectations for me.  Still, I was more feminine than those expectations and more performative (I liked doing impressions of men and women from film and television).  It was only acceptable at the time because I made him and everyone else laugh.  I also realize now how lucky I was to be able to do that, how I sort of tricked my way out of having to be what my father and many others wanted me to be.    Regardless, this video made me think of that.  It made me realize how privileged I was both to be able to do those things with little question and how much I take for granted now.  Now-a-days I just wear whatever with little thought.  I suppose I put on a bad performance because I'm not all that interested in it, but that's partially because it seems like no one cares about it.  I'm just not questioned and scrutinized like so many others are.  Thank you for the video and I'm going to have to become a Patreon supporter because all your videos are fantastic.  Thought provoking.

I wonder what Judith Butler would think of the phrase 'gender is performance'. She's pretty outspoken on the difference between saying 'gender is performed' and 'gender is performative', largely because the former conjures up the idea of 'playing a role'. I don't claim to fully understand what she means since I don't have a background in academic philosophy like Natalie, but in an interview she said that the 'performativity' referred more to creating a 'series of effects'.

If I can pose a counter argument on Tabby's behalf (about 13 1/2 mins in):   On the flip side, if someone else calls you a helicopter, does that make you a helicopter? Sure, people can call you things that are hurtful, and sometimes it hurts because it's a painful truth, but the source of the hurt in a case like that is the fact that it doesn't reflect the inner experience being a human (or a cat, I suppose); it's because you're not a helicopter that you would be bothered by being called one, and not some secret painful inner truth of being a helicopter.   Ergo, misgendering can be a kind of perceived robbing of gender, but it is only painful *because* of how it contradicts the inner experience, so it isn't an actual robbing of gender so much as a perceptual one - not a painful truth, but a painful *untruth*. Aesthetics can help others (and maybe the self) to navigate away from such untruth, but even in the absence of the aesthetic and the benefits that come with it, the inner truth is still what it is. In this way, the effort to stamp out misgendering is really an effort to promote truth, aesthetics or no. Does that track...?   I mean I guess that's where they end up going anyway, I was just a little surprised that Tabby didn't seize the opportunity to flip the helicopter analogy back around.   And the notion that we're living in too much of an aesthetic age to rely wholly on a philosophical approach was... well, a pretty painful truth that does have to be wrestled with to some degree. Point taken there, I guess. Oof.  Anyway, excellent video once again, love it!

'I'm actually a lady who used to be a man dressed as a man dressed as a lady'  That's pretty easy to explain really. It's an interesting use of varying definitions being used in conjunction with each other to make a simple statement seem complex or even unexplainable. I'll break it down by replacing the definitions for the words.   Im actually (a person who exhibits/embraces characteristics and mannerisms which are commonly associated with femininity) who used to be a (person who exhibits/embraces characteristics and mannerisms which are commonly associated with masculinity) portraying a (person who exhibits/embraces characteristics and mannerisms which are commonly associated with masculinity)  dressed as (a person who exhibits/embraces characteristics and mannerisms which are commonly associated with femininity).  Interestingly the entire sentence could also be preceded by 'I am a male who is actually a lady....' and still be entirely true while also providing some concrete and practical knowledge unlike the original which tells us nothing of any use to anyone besides yourself.

If we're just fighting for the right of passing transwomen, rather than every nonbinary and nonconforming person, we're going to end up alone very quickly. So yeah, if the goal is to let the luckiest few get the same misogynistic treatment cis women get, that works. But if that's the goal, I'd rather go down fighting the real fight for everyone oppressed. I'm not saying the point about aesthetics isn't valid, but we should fight under the aesthetics we want to be recognized under, not those they want to impose on us, because we'll only win the rights to be the fake self we showed.
